- Blueprint introduced in commit message is related with neutron project. IMO, will be better to create different blueprint for heat, where you describe, that you plan to add some resources from neutron project (current link may be used for providing details about new resources. I mean, that will be good to reference on existing blueprint in neutron from your new blueprint in heat).

- Current patch contain a lot of new objects (resources) and so big change is very difficult for review. I suggest to split it on several patches.'}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2014-05-16 11:15:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Add bootstrap remote logs to rotation

Current rotation templates are missing the 2nd level
of directories inside of /var/log/remote/*/
and that is an issue due to bootstrap logs are residing
there as well.

poke ci2
Closes-bug: #1349809

Change-Id: If8f61220eeb897faf3ba403833564de85718b03d
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Improve logging when python-guestfs/libguestfs isn't working

Bumped from debug to warn level, as most often refers to
missing python-guestfs package or other libguestfs misconfiguration,
and the fallback path is usually not desired.

Closes-bug: 1240339
Change-Id: I5d90a3ea109e79fe17221c001f94d49d599048ba

commit_message:
Cleanup README.rst

There are two harmless typos in the README.rst
'OpenStackclient' => 'OpenStack Client'
'python-*client' => the '*' is being interpreted as a link

Change-Id: Ie813e220c3c150f46edb2c93f94e8bb78bdb0013
Closes-Bug: #1350518

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

Change hardcoded ip to localhost

This patch just changes the hardcoded ip to local host. We should really
make this configurable through congress.conf but this will probably be
fine for now.

commit_message:
Use auth_token from keystonemiddleware

auth_token middleware in python-keystoneclient is deprecated and has
been moved to the keystonemiddleware repo.

test_keystone_middleware_conf and
test_keystone_middleware_parse_conffile were removed. These tests
were relying on undocumented behavior (how the config options turn
into attributes). This doesn't work anymore since the
keystonemiddleware version doesn't provide any public API other than
calling it as a wsgi app, and then doesn't document what internal
operations it will do when called so isn't safe to be called in
unit tests. Tests verifying that the auth_token middleware can read
its config options should be done in keystonemiddleware.

Closes-Bug: #1342274

Change-Id: I1aadbe24db63eb2507b088cd53886d7f2e192cab

commit_message:
Fixes the failure of updating or deleting image empty property

When property protection feature enabled, end user couldn't uses
Glance v2 API to update or delete a property of an image successfully
which value is empty, client will receive a http 500 error and a
relevant error log could be found in glance-api service log.

Closes-bug: #1332103

Change-Id: I1f9f181cea714e6ba26388d125bb7023e7a14305
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Fix enums usage for postgres in migrations

For downgrade with postgres it is not enough to just drop_table if
table contains enums. The enums should be removed separately after
deleting the table.

Also, if a migration uses an existing enum then postgresql needs some
specific code to re-use this enum.

Closes-Bug: #1243213

Change-Id: Ie5bb8282f7b289c917679192a0d722eb29b8d30f

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be

commit_message:
Audited attribute for policy update not changing

Updating firewall policy with shared, name or description is not changing the
audited attribute to false. Modified firewall policy update to make audited
to false.

Change-Id: Ic3f3e08190dcdaa8f4ecda729bdb2fdf1bdadc52
Closes-bug: 1327063

commit_message:
Add devstack integration files

This patch introduces integration files that we need in order to
use devstack to configure congress automatically for us. This is
an important step as we need this automation to integrate CI testing.

This patch also changes the .gitignore file as by default the path
in here is match globally in the project thus lib in .gitignore was
preventing me from adding the contrib/devstack/lib/congress file.

closes-bug: 1343545
Change-Id: I03613270cd1c8b5910499e74398a39a5167bae69

commit_message:
Use correct section for log message if interface_driver import fails

If import of interface_driver in namespace_driver fails then message for
logger raises exception because of taking interface_driver from haproxy
section while actual interface_driver is in default section.

Closes-Bug: #1350320
Change-Id: Ic1e73c0cdccb2fff02f2adfbad677503c29ba88a

commit_message:
Fix rollback failure when updating stack

When building oldstack in rollback, self.env doesn't match self.t, then
the validating will fail, but oldstack is useless in rollback, so we don't
need to build it in rollback.

Change-Id: Iab17824d108d565126c1dd0338fefc9a5ee4f47b
Closes-Bug: #1308883

commit_message:
Allow unsharing a network used as gateway/floatingip

If network has ports that connect it as gateway to another network, such
as an external network, or "floating ip" ports it should still be
possible to "unshare" it since these ports represent usage of the
network as an external network, not as a VM data network.

Change-Id: Ic33ae7ac193e4fc9fe06a4cfd579a4aacf0e6354
Closes-bug: #1293184

commit_message:
Further cleanup of reservations index

It was discovered that the duplicate index checking does not work

commit_message:
Allow Resources to select paths from attributes

Previously when get_attr included a path to select from the attribute, the
selection was done by the get_attr intrinsic function. Starting with the
Juno version of HOT, move control of this to the resource plugin, so that
individual resources (particularly ResourceGroup) can handle it themselves.

Related-Bug: #1341048
Change-Id: Ic3dc94a99a19e28a4f775198ff6e960e2efb8256

commit_message:
Sync requirements with upstream

$ cd /opt/stack/requirements
$ python update.py /opt/stack/congress

This is also required for devstack integration as devstack runs these
commands on stack.sh and stops if a project is out of sync.

Change-Id: I9057fbefb18fc09ff70278f9db152327f94b37a0

commit_message:
Add OpenStack policy integration bits

This patch adds the openstack policy integration bits which we can use to
enforce which congress api calls can be made by a normal tenant
vs admin tenant. Today the default policy.json defaults to requiring an
admin to make an API call. Though, for example, one could add the following
to policy.json to allow a non-admin tenant to create a data-source:

"create_data_sources": "rule:regular_user"

This patch also renames Context to RequestContext and drops some unneeded code.

Related to blueprint keystone-integration

Change-Id: I7fe17938ba6814df3679d9d9fd0ed1cd4fc3771f

commit_message:
Shorten case studies section titles

Remove the part after the colon for most case study section titles. This
information is now redundant with the chapter title that they fall under.
Keep the colon / subtitle for the one case study that exists as a stand
alone chapter as that still provides a useful purpose. Once that one is
split into the preceeding chapters, it can also follow this new convention.

Change-Id: I36f905abeb4c4e4278fdc25d1850c38629a20619

@greg,

it's not a need, more of a useability thing. devtest_variables should define what is avaiable for tweaking for a user going through devtest (imo anyway). further, those should be exported so they can get picked up by write-tripleorc so that a user can save their customizations.

i don't really understand the decoupling bit...devtest_testenv.sh is highly reliant on devtest_variables already for any customization you want to do, as is setup-seed-vm, which devtest_testenv calls. There are several variables in those scripts that are documented in devtest_variables. Regardless, the change here doesn't make anything more coupled as I added the same default for NODE_CNT as existed before, devtest_testenv is still executable stand alone. At most, the comment documenting the option is now only in devtest_variables, which I could replicate in devtest_testenv I suppose."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-25 15:11:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Verified

http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2014-07-25 15:11:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

(1 comment)

To me, this seems like a step toward rationalise-ui.  We centralize all of the configurable bits rather than having documentation of them scattered throughout the various scripts.  Once we get around to implementing rationalise-ui, we rip out all of the VAR=${VAR:-default} and make it VAR=get_value_from_rational_ui(var_name).  Actually, we could probably rip out all of these things from _variables and just read them in the appopriate places, but either way having all of these definitions in one place is only going to make that easier.

tldr: I think this is fine.  The only comment I would have is that all of the NODE_* variables might be appropriate to move too.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-25 15:12:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add vars to devtest_variables.sh

Adds the DEPLOY_* and NODE_CNT vars to devtest_variables.sh, and makes
sure they are exported. Exporting them will allow them to be saved by
write-tripleorc, and their values are important enough to be saved and
reused via the tripleorc file.

Change-Id: I043ced247827b10455826c413775be3ddc4d3473

commit_message:
Don't use PRUN on a command that has a pipe "|"

Otherwise we get binary content (images) in the log file.

Change-Id: I4f1d1bc22adc145f7e7ee668538afdac72ac9e6a
Closes-bug: #1350645

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-29 18:51:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm softening a bit after mulling this over, but a few points:

1. This is dependent on an abandoned patch, is that going to be dropped as a dependency?

2. The conversion to use objects (my patch) is what changed things really so that you get the traceback in the logs, which is reported in the associated bug:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/64914/8/nova/api/openstack/compute/contrib/simple_tenant_usage.py

The code used to just return timeutils.utcnow() when dtstr was None, but now it will try to parse None and you get the traceback.  So I think the else is probably the right logic, we just missed it in my patch.

3. The commit message is basically saying that start/end being optional are OK, but given the API docs that's not true - HOWEVER, I'd argue that the code has always been allowing those to be optional despite the docs, so to change that (what my patch did) breaks the API's backward compatibility with Havana, so this is a decent fix - maybe that just needs to be clarified in the commit message?"}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2014-06-23 06:49:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-23 06:49:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

_parse_datetime in os-simple-tenant-usage incorrectly attempts
to parse the datetime string even when it is None. As a result
a 400 BadRequest is returned. This has the overall effect of making
the start and end datetime parameters compulsory when they are meant
to be optional.

This fixes that bug so the original intent of a default of utcnow being
used occurs when the start or end datetime string is not supplied.

I believe this change meets the API change guidelines as it fixes a bug and
does not change the result of any previously successful request.

commit_message:
Fix _parse_datetime in simple tenant usage extension

_parse_datetime in os-simple-tenant-usage incorrectly attempts
to parse the datetime string even when it is None. As a result
a 400 BadRequest is returned. This has the overall effect of making
the start and end datetime parameters compulsory when they are meant
to be optional.

Note that this restores the behavior where start/end are optional which is
in contradiction to the API docs, but is the long standing API behaviour.
This was an API change which was accidentally applied in commit
I8e0e870727d687da165c809ffb7a4456bff81122 as part of some nova internal
changes but not picked up by the unitests

Change-Id: I00427379dc7aa39770f9a16ff026addb6e311735
Closes-Bug: 1300972

commit_message:
Fix --heat-env

There is a missing ',' for the getopt for help, causing "heat-env:help"
to be parsed as one option. This prevents --heat-env from working.

Change-Id: I10596c380645d2a58f013932e1c5b75675eee22f

commit_message:
Fix swift-dispersion-populate bug when using SimpleClient class

Commit 7fcbbebb changed the internal client a little bit and removed the
class variable self.attempts in SimpleClient. This is currently still
needed in swift-dispersion-populate to track the number of retries, thus
re-adding it again.

Closes-Bug: 1351323
Change-Id: I98ba6441607158b34708b2dbb2d1a63788681d63

commit_message:
Permit non-loopback guest access to Rabbit.

Recent versions of RabbitMQ have defaulted to only permitting the guest
user to connect from the loopback address.

Many elements have yet to consume rabbit accounts - until the configuration
of per-service (or per-server) accounts is finalised, ensure that newer
rabbit versions will be backwardly-compatible with the old behaviour.

Change-Id: I30e0156862c5672aef3e31a6919c8fe1957e3a02
Related-bug: #1315474
Related-bug: #1317778

commit_message:
Commit kafka reads once the item was persisted

In order to continue using the Kafka High Consumer API, the disruptor
was removed. This allows a direct call to to kafka to commit the offsets
when items are flushed.

Different ConsumerConnectors had to be created for Metrics and Alarms
so the offsets could be committed separately

Changed configuration to match the new model.  Remove configuration
parameters that were no longer needed

Changed the name Disruptor to Pipeline

Allow only one EventHandler per pipeline

Added code to flush the Metrics and Alarms, and shutdown the Kafka ConsumerConnections on a normal shutdown. This keeps the persister from losing Metrics and Alarms.

Made measurementTimeStampSimpleDateFormat not static since SimpleDateFormat is not thread safe

Changed some logging debug statements so Strings weren't created if debug not on

Created FlushableHandler as a base class and moved duplicate code into it from MetricHandler and AlarmStateTransitionHistoryHandler

Change-Id: Id31a1d148f8e796f5be483dd02544be49c009b18

Changed MetricHandler to take MetricEnvelope[]

Change-Id: Ifabbe253cc0163f150ada2252a41a5d9fb9ab423

commit_message:
change assert(Not)Equals to assert(Not)Equal

According to http://docs.python.org/2/library/unittest.html
assert(Not)Equals is a deprecated alias of assert(Not)Equal.
Enabled H234 check.

Change-Id: I201559be7ab038889f585f5d20fd1a2c6f606182

commit_message:
Add examples for development of Fuel

Adding a new page to Fuel development
documentation including two specific examples -
the addition of Zabbix role, and the addition of
support for Mellanox hardware.

Change-Id: Ib5f7df8cc0c94580bc8c3deff61c6934dd701079
Implements: blueprint fuel-web-docs-dev-env-restructure

commit_message:
Do not run haproxy in chroot

Chroot prevents haproxy from logging into /dev/log
and that is an issue. There is no need to run
it in chroot as well.

Closes-bug: #1350835

commit_message:
Fix for SSH method of OSTF tests

In SSH method of OSTF tests address of controller node is chosen
as the first from list of controller nodes.
It may not work when we have a few controller nodes (HA mode) and one
of controller nodes went away. Now controller node is chosen
from list of controller nodes online.

Closes-Bug: #1346864

Change-Id: I74801a352c4a96e1fa1c254fd49db19d6584b427

Add bash completion to glance client

Currently glance client does not support command completion.
The intention is to add this functionality to the client

blueprint add-bash-completion

Change-Id: Ia13a119967b15d44918a1f7d51b9f142640865cc

This patch adds the bits needed for keystone support integration. In order
to run congress-server without keystone support set:
auth_strategy=noauth in congress.conf

The general structure of congress-api server code now works in the following
way:

congress/server/congress-server loads the paste configuration file:
If configured to use keystone requests to congress server go through
the following pipeline:

keystone = request_id catch_errors authtoken keystonecontext congress_api

request_id - pipeline sets a request ID in the header for each API request and
adds it to the API response.

catch_errors -  catches all exceptions from subsequent applications in WSGI
pipeline to hide internal errors from API response.

authtoken - Verifies that incoming client requests have valid tokens by
validating tokens with the auth service.

keystonecontext - Converts keystone headers in request to a request context
object.

congress_api - the ApiApplication that handles congress api requests

Implements: blueprint keystone-integration

Change-Id: Ie703e0b5aec156415d7432888131bf5e24db8fd6

commit_message:
Add keystone support

This patch adds the bits needed for keystone support integration. In order
to run congress-server without keystone support set:
    auth_strategy=noauth in congress.conf

Implements: blueprint keystone-integration

Change-Id: Ie703e0b5aec156415d7432888131bf5e24db8fd6

Fix template and reST online renderer links

commit_message:
Skip test_rescope_token

There are several problems with revocation events in Keystone and
the test is currently failing on postgres. There's several fixes
proposed in Keystone to fix these but until they're merged this
test isn't working.

Change-Id: I9182d542fae0b4a5280dc482300203f84c8f4d8c
Closes-Bug: #1351026

commit_message:
Encode should be called only for strings

If not string provided as arg to print_to_output
it should not be encoded, and lets assume that proper unicode handling
will be done in custom print_method

Change-Id: If0c03571ccc7513fe85c38477ad9750ad9d82e97
Closes-Bug: #1330485

commit_message:
Added monasca python components to the global requirements

These are packages which are part of the monitoring solution
being developed by HP. The project is part of both StackForge and the
Commercial edition of Helion.

Change-Id: Ibe03b74745af2c19846d5f929ee7f557ca217777

commit_message:
Fixes hyper-v volume attach when host is AD member

The domain name gets added to the initiator name used by the host
if it's an Active Directory member.

Currently the method which gets the initiator name does not take
this into account when retrieving the default initiator name.

Trying to use a wrong initiator name will lead to an exception when
trying to log in to the according iSCSI target.

This patch simply appends the domain name (when the host is an AD
member) to the initiator name used to log in to iSCSI targets.

Closes-Bug: #1328870
(cherry-picked from commit 0a7527c71228c8e776ad40cedd2cf137fd99f43d)

Change-Id: Ifbe762c685e46081059a01043431b2c4ac5473fc

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but nova unittests don't currently pass

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but nova unittests don't currently pass
with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Change-Id: I7e2db17668bf522eb9ff4d77eb1ba47be39b52fb
Co-Authored-By: Clark Boylan <clark.boylan@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Add pyngus for oslo.messaging

pyngus is an AMQP 1.0 messaging library.  It will be used by the
oslo.messaging project to implement a new AMQP 1.0-compatible driver.

The blueprint for this new driver: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo.messaging/+spec/amqp10-driver-implementation

Change-Id: Iff0684de2e72d39d065d549447e6d59464b914d5
Partially-Implements: blueprint amqp10-driver-implementation

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but nova unittests don't currently pass
with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Change-Id: I7e2db17668bf522eb9ff4d77eb1ba47be39b52fb
Co-Authored-By: Clark Boylan <clark.boylan@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Make default extension path relative to pybasedir

Load extensions from the trove base dir regardless of the current working
directory.

Closes-Bug: 1316195
Change-Id: I7f75998a357d1fb2033ed944c552fd856c2f2939

commit_message:
Fixes rbd backend image size

The original fix for bug 1219658 introduced a factor of 1024 error
in the resulting rbd image size.

Fix bug #1219658

Change-Id: I3ec53b3617d52f75784ebb3b0dad92ca815f8876
Co-authored-by: Nikola Dipanov <ndipanov@redhat.com>
Signed-off-by: Haomai Wang <haomai@unitedstack.com>
(cherry picked from commit f27ca3134743b45e55afd6c73abbb83c87ba8489)

Hi Mark and other reviewers,

I understand that there is fair amount of code for a one shot review.

But I feel that the code that has been submitted is a fairly cohesive unit and as such best reviewed as one. This patch introduces a framework for configuring services. It will enable patches of future services to be much shorter in size and reduce reviewing time.

I also made an effort to break this into smaller pieces like one for the config agent and another for the routing service helper and CSR device driver. It was not possible as they made use of common pieces like the device_status and constants in the cisco constants, which needed to be in both patches. There was the additional difficulty that separating them produces fair amount of rework in the unit tests too.
Hence in the interest of time, it will be highly appreciated if it can be presented and reviewed together.

I am adding a short overview of the modules/files to assist the reviewing process and highlight the important areas.

a) cfg_agent.py -> the main config agent process. It acts as a container for service helpers, triggers the periodic processing of different services.
b) service_helpers/routing_svc_helper.py -> service level processing for a particular service. Thus they embed the logic to process the service level resources and convert them to driver level configuration actions. This patch introduces the routing service helper which processes routing service. As an example, this will process the router dict, detect a router interface was added and issue a driver command, driver.internal_network_added()
c)device_drivers/csr1kv -> modules with configuration logic of the CSR1kv device. Most of this is IOS snippets and code to convert the neutron router info to Netconf IOS commands.
d) device_status.py -> logic for checking health of a device. Unreachable devices are added to a backlog and periodically rechecked. If device is suspected dead, it is reported back to the plugin.

As such I think cfg_agent.py and routing_svc_helper.py would require the most attention.

Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 7021, 'date': '2014-07-03 22:11:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Configuration agent for Cisco devices

A generic config agent for configuring L3+ services in Cisco devices.

This patch targets specifically configuration of L3 fuctionality,
namely routing, NAT and floatingIPs in Cisco CSR1kv virtual appliance.

Implements blueprint: cisco-config-agent
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/cisco-config-agent

Change-Id: Ic887a93480eca0b56049c67e32c98658e3a4427f

"Raising nova exceptions has been moved to

commit_message:
Move novaclient exceptions to heat.tests.v1_1.fakes

Applying novaclient exceptions fix from commit:
9850832da563c1113e121b99d38feb21af9daa8d

"Raising nova exceptions has been moved to
heat.tests.v1_1.fakes.fake_exception since it is actually impossible
to directly create a nova exception object which works on both
novaclient 2.17 and (yet to be released) 2.18.
nova.exceptions.from_response is stable across novaclient releases
so all test exceptions are now raised using from_response."

Change-Id: I0c5e58ffdd3eb13b9a87df22f1c5e06cec972913
Closes-Bug: #1322098

commit_message:
Make project optional during User creation

For keystone V3, the default project is an optional field.
A Domain Admin account may only be interacting with Keystone
and does not need to be associated with a Project. Project
association is required for Domain Users that needs to use
services other than Keystone. Making this optional allows the
Cloud Admin to setup a Domain Admin account without the project
association.

Change-Id: I20dff330ce3fcbbb3be7e8512df66c01aa5e3458
Partial-Implements: blueprint domain-admin-support

commit_message:
Install gettext from apt on Trusty (Ubuntu 14.04)

The binary 'msgfmt' is not installed as part of python-gettext for Trusty
(Ubuntu 14.04), so gettext needs to be installed from apt.

Change-Id: I415814559d82be453e978a0d92a0cdb38f105683
Closes-Bug: 1331328

commit_message:
Update Twitter Bootstrap to version 3

Updated to bootstrap 3.2.0
back to v3.1.1
fix base-line-height variable
Revamped grid system
Replaced help-inline with help-block
Change .control-group to .form-group
Add column widths to horizontal form labels and .controls, remove .controls class
Datepicker form fix
Add btn-default to btn elements with no other color
Topbar switcher fix
Rename button sizes
Replace alert-error with alert-danger
Removed alert-block
Alerts fixing
Updated LinkAction and Action table actions to define icon, replaced btn-default icon with glyphicon
Replaced icons with glyphicons, removed btn-icon styling from horizon.scss
change Button Icons text in customizing docs
Fixed table header
Fix page_header h2 margin
Nav accordion fix
Tables fix
Modal fixes
added form-control class to input and selects
Forms fixes
Workflow modal fix
Fix quota bar
updated customizing docs
removed unused styling from horizon.scss
make datepicker form inline
fix table filter styling
added btn-danger to terminate instances button
fixed loading spinner
form fields and validations
Created bootstrap_form_field filter and template to render bootstrap forms properly
Style up the datepicker
Fixed failing test cases

Implements: blueprint bootstrap-update

Added Sahara Image context

This context will be responsable for uploading and tagging an image for
Sahara clusters' benchmarks.

Change-Id: I9b89805e35f48212ac49ec94aa02ffc14d3ab535

Fix misspellings in openstack-nose

Fix misspellings detected by:
* pip install misspellings
* git ls-files | grep -v locale | misspellings -f -

Closes-Bug: #1257295

commit_message:
Fixes HP LeftHand driver with Paramiko 1.13.0

With Paramiko 1.13.0, the method exec_command now returns Unicode.
This causes a problem when the driver tries to build the XML returned
from the LeftHand array. The XML header returned from the array defines
the encoding as encoding=UTF-8. Therefore, we must now ensure the
encoding passed to the parser is utf-8.

closes-bug: #1298608
(cherry picked from commit 57e8cdb9dd8e24919bc2243438a6bded53491b3e)

Conflicts:

	cinder/tests/test_hplefthand.py
	cinder/volume/drivers/san/hp_lefthand.py

Change-Id: I7b504626e2d9a0ee2b62820b11f56eb136e31987

commit_message:
Remove dbapi calls from agent driver

This commit removes dbapi calls from the agent driver in favor
of using objects. It also cleans up the object code a bit, and
adds some test objects to ironic.tests.objects.utils.

commit_message:
Fixes ConfigDrive bug on Windows

Files must be written specifying "wb" instead of "w"
to support binary files on both Windows and Linux.

Closes-Bug: #1261585

(cherry-picked from commit 1fc9eafab43accc127044351106983e2cb215520)

Change-Id: I069845136df4a11b54c931a71575ca3efb9bc6d0

Enable overriding of Ceilometer storage backend

That is needed to have gate jobs running on different backends.

commit_message:
XenAPI: Fix declare definition

Some versions of bash do not initialise a variable with declare -a
therefore with set -u bash can terminate the script.

Be more verbose in declaring the array if it is not set

Change-Id: I6ec2b6e986aeffe539a2ab93432fa7af9e5a4f5d

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8091, 'date': '2014-07-24 14:03:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

Daniele,

  Here are my current thoughts on input/output sources.  Like Pozie Java actions, Spark jobs will just take arguments when the job execution is launched since the programs are really unconStrained -- they don't necessarily require input/output like an Oozie MapReduce job, for instance.

  Input/output specifiers will just be paths.  We can support whatever path formats Spark supports.  The Oozie stuff does this now -- you can have swift paths and absolute or relative hdfs paths.  This will be cleaner when we add a specific Spark job type.

  Yes, Spark needs to support swift paths.  Maybe we can get someone in the Spark community to do that work (or maybe some Sahara folks can join the community :) )

  I'm also thinking that we need something in the UI that allows you to select a data source object which will be used to supply the value for a particular argument.  That way, you can type a path, or click a data source object if you have one already that contains the right path (but this is another discussion with croberts)"}, {'account_id': 8091, 'date': '2014-07-24 20:18:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-24 20:18:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-18 01:11:41.000000000', 'message': 'Implement EDP for a Spark standalone cluster

This change adds an EDP engine for a Spark standalone cluster.
The engine uses the spark-submit script and various linux
commands via ssh to run, monitor, and terminate Spark jobs.

Currently, the Spark engine can launch "Java" job types (this is
the same type used to submit Oozie Java action on Hadoop clusters)

A directory is created for each Spark job on the master node which
contains jar files, the script used to launch the job, the
job's stderr and stdout, and a result file containing the exit
status of spark-submit.  The directory is named after the Sahara
job and the job execution id so it is easy to locate.  Preserving
these files is a big help in debugging jobs.

A few general improvements are included:
* engine.cancel_job() may return updated job status
* engine.run_job() may return job status and fields for job_execution.extra
in addition to job id
* a "Spark home" config setting has been added to the Spark plugin, defaulted
to /opt/spark

Still to do:
* use "Spark home" in place of /opt/spark throughout (new CR)
* create a proper Spark job type (new CR)
* make the job dir location on the master node configurable (new CR)
* add something to clean up job directories on the master node (new CR)
* allows users to pass some general options to spark-submit itself (new CR)
* add some unit tests for the Spark engine

blueprint and spec in progress

Change-Id: I2c84e9cdb75e846754896d7c435e94bc6cc397ff

commit_message:
Implement EDP for a Spark standalone cluster

This change adds an EDP engine for a Spark standalone cluster.
The engine uses the spark-submit script and various linux
commands via ssh to run, monitor, and terminate Spark jobs.

Currently, the Spark engine can launch "Java" job types (this is
the same type used to submit Oozie Java action on Hadoop clusters)

A directory is created for each Spark job on the master node which
contains jar files, the script used to launch the job, the
job's stderr and stdout, and a result file containing the exit
status of spark-submit.  The directory is named after the Sahara
job and the job execution id so it is easy to locate.  Preserving
these files is a big help in debugging jobs.

A few general improvements are included:
* engine.cancel_job() may return updated job status
* engine.run_job() may return job status and fields for job_execution.extra
in addition to job id

Still to do:
* create a proper Spark job type (new CR)
* make the job dir location on the master node configurable (new CR)
* add something to clean up job directories on the master node (new CR)
* allows users to pass some general options to spark-submit itself (new CR)

Partial implements: blueprint edp-spark-standalone

Change-Id: I2c84e9cdb75e846754896d7c435e94bc6cc397ff

commit_message:
Pass the parent's registry into child stacks

We make sure that there is no infinite recursion by not repeating
a TemplateResource within a resources inheritance.

Change-Id: I1ffa66886923b15b52a8075089dd4042f0a55862
Closes-Bug: #1297396

commit_message:
Turn periodic tasks off in all unit tests

We shouldn't rely on periodic tasks to randomly run in unit tests,
instead if we need them to run we should explicitly call them out.

Change-Id: I35850c47288e50d3146771dc7a9a54d62e36c3cf
Related-Bug: 1311778

[{'created': '2014-04-24 22:01:55.000000000', 'message': "Fix handling multiple WWPNs on preferred FC node

There was a bug in the code that checked to see if the
appropriate WWPN for a preferred node was available on the storage
host in intialize_connection.  It was assumed that there would only
ever be one preferred WWPN.  The code just checked to see if the list of
preferred WWPNs was in the list of available WWPNs.  This would only work
if all of the WWPNs were available on the storage host.  This resulted in
volumes not being able to be mounted when they should have been
available.

This fix changes the check of the preferred WWPNs to check each
item in the list until one is found.  The first one found is used
as the target WWPN.  If no match is found, the old default behavior
of selecting the first available WWPN is used.  I have added a
warning message for this case as it is quite possible that this
won't work in the user's environment as was the case that uncovered
this bug.

Note that this change is only relevant for systems that are not using
multipath as systems that use multipath don't choose one WWPN, they
just send the whole available list back.

Change-Id: I8d3239da24a8f9fbd8309ba5c90b05b29a068754
(cherry picked from commit 9bfc5b0bf58ecb7de5904cbd41db6de7330187e3)
Close-bug: 1308298

commit_message:
Fix handling multiple WWPNs on preferred FC node

There was a bug in the code that checked to see if the
appropriate WWPN for a preferred node was available on the storage
host in intialize_connection.  It was assumed that there would only
ever be one preferred WWPN.  The code just checked to see if the list of
preferred WWPNs was in the list of available WWPNs.  This would only work
if all of the WWPNs were available on the storage host.  This resulted in
volumes not being able to be mounted when they should have been
available.

This fix changes the check of the preferred WWPNs to check each
item in the list until one is found.  The first one found is used
as the target WWPN.  If no match is found, the old default behavior
of selecting the first available WWPN is used.  I have added a
warning message for this case as it is quite possible that this
won't work in the user's environment as was the case that uncovered
this bug.

Note that this change is only relevant for systems that are not using
multipath as systems that use multipath don't choose one WWPN, they
just send the whole available list back.

Change-Id: I8d3239da24a8f9fbd8309ba5c90b05b29a068754
(cherry picked from commit 9bfc5b0bf58ecb7de5904cbd41db6de7330187e3)
Close-bug: 1308298

commit_message:
Debug 'Cannot allocate memory'

Several jobs fails with [OSError] Cannot allocate memory,
but it is not clear why. Is  it caused by multiple run away process,
or just on process become fat.

Adding line to cleanup_host to save the final process list including
the memory usage.

Change-Id: Ic7455d689869092703974512d14bd121e4b44f1b

commit_message:
Prevent clean-up of migrating instances on compute init

During compute manager startup init_host is called. One
of the functions this carries out is to delete instance
data that doesn't belong to this host this function only
checks if the local instance belongs to the host or not.
It doesn't check the task_state. This could result in the
loss of all instance data if it occured at the wrong
point during live migration.

This change checks if the task_state of the instance to
be deleted is MIGRATING and if so it does not delete the
instance. Similarily for the task state RESIZE_MIGRATING.

This change adjust little about the unit test according to
actual code path in icehouse.
Conflicts:
	nova/tests/compute/test_compute_mgr.py

Change-Id: Ia8c67acf93d71af868907f0711dcc1dfe103560c
Closes-Bug: 1319797
(cherry picked from commit 340cae5466eaf5568c4f0eecb2a2fa7cdbcc0ba4)

commit_message:
Correct the region table to be InnoDB and UTF8

The region table was not specified as being InnoDB or UTF8 under
mysql initially. The migration will fail if the defaults for MySQL
are not set correctly. A new method has been added to the
migration_helpers module to detect and correct the InnoDB / UTF8
specific issue with the region table.

Change-Id: I374c3dd46a4292e8f9e74ef75a8bb463b951f135
Closes-Bug: #1334779

commit_message:
TLS capability extension implementation for lbaas v2

Including extension and db model modifications
Including db model unit testing
Including alembic migration
Including usage of new common module for Barbican TLS containers API interaction

Change-Id: Ia8f90a2be791d7922f93d6d3fbadf32ab66562c9
Implements: blueprint lbaas-ssl-termination

commit_message:
Add the rpc base environment for rally rpc manager

1. Add `workers` table to record the rally-worker status.
2. Sync the necessary modules for service from other openstack projects.
3. Add RPC manager named rally-worker.

Change-Id: Idcbbba776ec030dbf1461c53982f328d6336d398

commit_message:
Handle unauthorized exception in NailgunClient

Move authorization using keystone client to the
HTTPClient class and update security token in
case of getting '401 Unauthorized' error.

Change-Id: Ieb754a7f4d718e971216dcc995e47e107853798f
Closes-bug: #1350836

'}, {'created': '2014-07-30 16:31:55.000000000', 'message': 'add client code for OSProfiler

This patch implements basic client code for OSProfiler, which contains:
 * osprofiler.cmd.cliutils - module with utils for client code
 * osprofiler.cmd.commands - module with all commands. Each group of
   commands should inherit from `osprofiler.cmd.commands.BaseCommand` class
 * osprofiler.cmd.exc - module for clients exceptions
   (implemented exceptions: CommandError)
 * osprofiler.cmd.shell - module with basic shell class(`OSProfilerShell`),
   which append ceilometer and identity arguments groups, discover all cli
   commands in `osprofiler.cmd.commands`
 * osprofiler.cmd.template.html - html-template for command
   "osprofiler results show"

TODO:
 1) Move client code into separate library
 2) Add more complex tests

Change-Id: If4bd50658c594793fe97e8ba1c9867694aa46ff4

commit_message:
Add entry point for OSProfiler, that display traces

This patch implements basic client code for OSProfiler, which contains:
 * osprofiler.cmd.cliutils - module with utils for client code
 * osprofiler.cmd.commands - module with all commands. Each group of
   commands should inherit from `osprofiler.cmd.commands.BaseCommand` class
   (implemented commands: `results show`)
 * osprofiler.cmd.exc - module for clients exceptions
   (implemented exceptions: CommandError)
 * osprofiler.cmd.shell - module with basic shell class(`OSProfilerShell`),
   which append ceilometer and identity arguments groups, discover all cli
   commands in `osprofiler.cmd.commands`.
 * osprofiler.cmd.template.html - html-template for command
   "osprofiler trace show"

Change-Id: If4bd50658c594793fe97e8ba1c9867694aa46ff4

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 9659, 'date': '2014-07-31 17:20:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 9622, 'date': '2014-07-31 17:44:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Hi Delcourt,

Not sure why we are adding space before colon?  I don't think we should alter the .po files since they will be automatically updated based on the source language."}, {'account_id': 11922, 'date': '2014-07-31 18:17:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Cindy, 

It's a French ponctuation rule; there is always a space before a colon. You can see its the case for the other french messages that includes a colon. Where should it be corrected?

Claire"}, {'account_id': 9622, 'date': '2014-07-31 18:39:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Claire,
Thanks for the clarification!
First, I think the bug should be reported to: https://bugs.launchpad.net/openstack-i18n

And then this seems like the way to fix it: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Documentation/Translation#Contribute_as_a_translator

(Hopefully this is correct info ^_^)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-31 18:54:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Thank you for your contribution! Cindy is correct, this should be fixed directly in Transifex. You're very welcome to join the i18n team and help OpenStack with translations, I'm sure the French team would love to have you!

There is additional information at https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/I18nTeam and the team also has a (low traffic) list at http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-i18n/, where all questions and discussions around translations are welcome. It should be possible also to simply make this one change in Transifex if that's all you'd like to contribute for now :)

I'm putting a -2 on this patch to make sure it doesn't merge in the meantime. There are 2 reasons:
- We have an automatic job that pulls all the translations from Transifex and submits them automatically as a patch, so your change would get overwritten during the next translation update
- Because the job is automatic, changing the files manually in parallel could cause merge conflicts and break it

The best way to go really is to work on Transifex directly. Please feel free to get in touch if you have any question, or pop up on IRC at #openstack-horizon if you need help. Cheers!"}, {'account_id': 11922, 'date': '2014-08-01 15:27:32.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Should be fixed directly in Transifex'}]

adds missing logging and reporting.

commit_message:
Upgrades, sync port binding scheme for containers with dockerctl

In 5.1 we use new port binding scheme
for containers, which is required
for access control feature where
we added new firewall rules.

* sync ports binding with dockerctl
* removed hack from docker engine
  where we converted lists in tuples
  because now we use python based config
  and we can use tuple based port binding
  format where it's required
* also to get rid of hack was required
  because it was impossible to bind
  several host system ports on one
  container's port

Change-Id: Ib3520a75362fe439dbe3dbe34e92da3f7b7307fa
Closes-bug: #1350385

commit_message:
Create system tests for vcenter verification

Added:
Create system tests for vcenter support and partially enhance some
classes/functions
1. In os_actions.py - some functions for nova client
2. In fuel_web_client.py - support of vCenter deploying
3. In run_tests.py - import tests for vCenter
4. In settings.py - import vCenter settings from environment
5. In base_test_case.py - new deploy case with one slave

Implements: blueprint vcenter-hv-full-scale-support
Change-Id: I18991dbb4b63bf9f407acdd05422032014889b3d

I tested this patch with mysql and postgresql with relatively small vxlan vni ranges (50 000) in case when the ml2_vxlan_allocations table was empty and several transactions tried to insert the same rows there.


For my I always got DBDeadlock: http://paste.openstack.org/show/87594/


And for postgresql - DBAPIError: http://paste.openstack.org/show/87595/


In case of mysql the problem was connected with lock which are set by the INSERT statement (see the INSERT section here: http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.0/en/innodb-locks-set.html)


I'm not so sure about postgresql, but I think it should be something similar."}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2014-08-01 14:34:01.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

commit_message:
Improve vxlan type driver initialization performance

Vxlan type driver may take long time to initialize vxlan allocation
table. Optimize delete db performance by deleting obsolete vxlans
in one query using SQL BETWEEN instead of deleting them bulk_size by
bulk_size and optimize existing vnis select.

Change-Id: Iae2853a5ef925eff38692f3b293d8d0734af2d28
Partial-Bug: #1324875
Partial-Bug: #1330562

commit_message:
Generate traffic for a given amount of time

Sending prefefined amount of packets for each interface:vlan pair
can still result in random verify_networks failures on heavily loaded
environments

- sender will generate traffic based on time provided with --duration option
  or from config file, defaults to 20 sec
- repeat option will be used to configure amount of packets per iface:vlan
  pair sended in each iteration, defaults to 2 packets

Change-Id: Ie92a3ea175ca2ae9f43e79f66b449366a1b68126
Partial-Bug: 1306705

commit_message:
Allow jquery as old as 1.7.2

Since we use jquery-migrate, Horizon will work both with jquery older
than 1.10 and newer. We don't use any 1.10-specific features, so it's
fine to allow older jquery versions.

This lets us package Horizon both for Debian (with jquery 1.7.2) and
for Fedora (with jquery 1.10.2).

Change-Id: Idb8ba9e8bfc522be7a953fa092aebc24adb0c9b3

commit_message:
Add retry of OSTF to all tests with restart

- Move method with running single OSTF test on volume creation
to fuel_web client
- Add check that volume creation passes to all tests with
restart

Closes-Bug: #1320248

Add retry of OSTF to all tests with restart

- Move method with running single OSTF test on volume creation
to fuel_web client
- Add check that volume creation passes to all tests with
restart

Closes-Bug: #1320248

commit_message:
Wait for keystone to become ready for floatingip creation

Wait for keystone service to become ready otherwise
haproxy reload can lead to haproxy returning
empty response and thus nova-floating-range provider
can not authorize with nova.

Change-Id: I8f9623411990679560b1694569dbb185883c4733
Closes-bug: #1351253

commit_message:
Fix not attribute '_periodic_last_run'

The ConductorManager class wasn't calling __init__ from
its parent object, causing an AttributeError exception
to be raised when accessing the attribute _periodic_last_run.
This attribute was initialized in the PeriodicTasks class.

Change-Id: Ieb850bf448f4b04be33c2cfecbac2de5925d6fda
Closes-Bug: #1351114

commit_message:
Fixes several failing mongo driver tests

Some mongodb tests were failing because the test suite was not
cleaning up the database in between runs. In the course of
fixing this bug, the tests in question were also DRY'd up between
the sqla and mongo drivers.

NOTE: This patch is a prerequisite for enabling mongo in the gate.
Change-Id: Iaa2a1cbd6a27c53a884c9e0260d48d77a7f198b9

commit_message:
Upgrades, remove saved version file on success

* created on_success method which upgrade
  script runs if upgrade succeed, don't
  fail upgrade in case of errors
* remove saved version files for all
  upgrades from working directories

It solves several problems:

1. user runs upgrade 5.0 -> 5.1 which fails
upgrade system saves version which we upgrade
from in file working_dir/5.1/version.yaml.
Then user runs upgrade 5.0 -> 5.0.1 which
successfully upgraded. Then user runs again
upgrade 5.0.1 -> 5.1, but there is saved file
working_dir/5.1/version.yaml which contains
5.0 version, and upgrade system thinks that
it's upgrading from 5.0 version, as result
it tries to make database dump from wrong
version of container.

2. without this hack user can run upgrade
second time and loose his data, this hack
prevents this case because before upgrade
checker will use current version instead
of saved version to determine version which
we run upgrade from.

Change-Id: I5e6ae6ba2ae2e60b9812e131d2a7c533f4a38ab6
Related-bug: #1349833

commit_message:
Upgrades, remove saved version file on success

* created on_success method which upgrade
  script runs if upgrade succeed, don't
  fail upgrade in case of errors
* remove saved version files for all
  upgrades from working directories

It solves several problems:

1. user runs upgrade 5.0 -> 5.1 which fails
upgrade system saves version which we upgrade
from in file working_dir/5.1/version.yaml.
Then user runs upgrade 5.0 -> 5.0.1 which
successfully upgraded. Then user runs again
upgrade 5.0.1 -> 5.1, but there is saved file
working_dir/5.1/version.yaml which contains
5.0 version, and upgrade system thinks that
it's upgrading from 5.0 version, as result
it tries to make database dump from wrong
version of container.

2. without this hack user can run upgrade
second time and loose his data, this hack
prevents this case because before upgrade
checker will use current version instead
of saved version to determine version which
we run upgrade from.

Change-Id: I5e6ae6ba2ae2e60b9812e131d2a7c533f4a38ab6
Related-bug: #1349833

I ran this code against my WIP for the ceilometer side of things: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/105486/ and ran into some issues in this code I thought worth reporting here:

* The default setting in ironic.conf for notification_driver is empty, which means it is possible to set send_sensor_data to True, and generate notifications, but not actually do anything with them.
* running ipmitool sdr -v looks like it can sometimes be very slow, it is hard to imagine it being efficient across a large number of nodes
* with debug=True the full output from ipmitool is logged creating a huge amount of output which gets in the way, ironically, of debugging
* Filtering available nodes on whether they are associated or not will miss registered nodes without instances.
* The service I'm getting test ipmitool data from is providing most sensor readings with a type of 'Sensor Type (Threshold)' which the current code does not accept.
* The 'event_type' being sent is 'sensordata', it might be better to have something like 'hardware.ipmi.metrics' or something like that. We need to agree so both sides have the same thing.

I still haven't got it quite working because of some problems with rpc/messaging config but will try again tomorrow, I've gone stupid now..."}, {'account_id': 8106, 'date': '2014-07-10 05:20:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

@Chris Dent,

Please kindly find my answers as below:

Q: Is "Current" the right name for that section? Watts are a unit of Power, and Current the units are amps.
A: Yes, I understand it is "Current" sensor, but the reading value is 'Watts' for some hardware systems.

Q: Is the relevant aspect of the the Fan section actually FanSpeed? Would the name of the associated metric be 'fan_speed' not just 'fan'?
A: Yes, it is Fan Speed in RPM, the data is returned from IPMI, so I think we can just keep the sensor name, and we have no exactly logic to do the name mapping.

Q:Is there a user_id or project_id associated with the notifications?
A: Yes, if nova instance has these properties, we can copy/populate them into our notification message.

Q:Can the notification include an event_type (e.g. 'hardware.ipmi.metrics.update')?
A: Do you want to add new field named 'event_type' and the value is 'hardware.ipmi.metrics.update', if yes, that is ok with me to support this with ironic code.


Welcome your comments, if I did not answer you, ping me in IRC or add more comments, thank you Chris.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-07-14 14:04:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': "Implements bp - Send Sensor Data to Ceilometer

We implement this bp for 'pxe_ipmitool' driver first, once our
ipminative lib is ready(the new release version>0.5.8) including
getting the sensor data command support, we will have another
'pxe_ipminative' driver implementation.

In this patch, we defined the base SensorInterface interface, and
enable it for pxe_ipmitool driver. We run 'ipmitool sdr -v' command
to get sensor data and parse and format to the message which will be
consumed by ceilometer and sent out via notification bus.

Change-Id: I2c072321a662db0162c938b7d4f3b59ba07d4e08
Implements: blueprint send-data-to-ceilometer

"}, {'created': '2014-07-14 02:27:57.000000000', 'message': "Implements send-data-to-ceilometer

This blueprint will define the sensor data collection interface and implement
a driver based on IPMI to collect sensor data and send them to Ceilometer.

The change covered by this patch:

1. Creates a new ironic.driver.base.ManagementInterface common method
*get_sensors_data* for gathering hardware sensor data.

2. Implements the interface into 'ipmitool' driver to gather data via IPMI
command call.

3. Adds periodic task to conductor which emits notification to Ceilometer by
an interval.

Spec: https://review.openstack.org/102435

Change-Id: I2c072321a662db0162c938b7d4f3b59ba07d4e08
Implements: blueprint send-data-to-ceilometer

commit_message:
Implements send-data-to-ceilometer

This patch will define the sensor data collection interface and implement
a driver based on IPMI to collect sensor data and send them to Ceilometer.

The change covered by this patch:

1. Creates a new ironic.driver.base.ManagementInterface common method
*get_sensors_data* for gathering hardware sensor data.

2. Implements the interface into 'ipmitool' driver to gather data via IPMI
command call.

3. Adds periodic task to conductor which emits notification to Ceilometer by
an interval.

Spec: https://review.openstack.org/102435

Change-Id: I2c072321a662db0162c938b7d4f3b59ba07d4e08
Implements: blueprint send-data-to-ceilometer

commit_message:
OpenStack Security Guide - Chapter 35: Grammatical and Format errors

Dissolving multiple grammatical errors, inclusive of awkward wording and improper punctuation; recharging "SSL" with "SSL/TLS"; removing whitespaces

Change-Id: Ib522c44ed7f0cb273a4b3bf39f50cd45e58ae0fb
Closes-Bug: #1342912

The js updated to work with new class.

Change-Id: Ib798d0e22ecb75ccda5e042b4348d650b64d89ae

commit_message:
Sync glossary from openstack-manuals

Import these changes from openstack-manuals:
d9d76a3 Update glossary meta data
33a6998 Fix glossary generation
ca9f0c8 add the glossterm "Bell-LaPadula modela".
ecbe652 Add Kilo to the glossary
305f9b9 User name fixes
80aaa7b Unified the syntax of the XML root element (glossary)
0b490a0 Fix DOCTYPE for glossary
c633f28 Fix some wrong UTF-8 characters
ce1777c Consistent terminology for XX-as-a-Service
95c9b4c Correct incorrect uses of "weight" and "weighting"

Change-Id: Ic448e01d62a22ed5d292552cf568a17ce153b032

commit_message:
Fix pipeline _get_context_from_last_execution()

 - change download_definition to get_definition
 - both the workbook and execution context return strings
   not dicts.

Change-Id: Ifb3069b0bf09618ba0e5941a725bf35ddb853e2c

commit_message:
XML support for multi-provider extension

Multi-provider extension does not support network creation using
xml body because segments markup are not correctly parsed, indeed
xml "plural" is not defined for segments/segment.

Change-Id: Ifb4d07b9abc54372acc4f08656bbffd081c0ff9d
Closes-bug: #1337263

commit_message:
devtest_overcloud: boot an instance from a volume

This patch updates our nova boot command to boot
an instance from a volume that is created on
the fly from a Glance image.

The motivation here is to expand our devtest
script so that it has some level of coverage
across Cinder which is commonly broken
in upstream TripleO.

Change-Id: Icd50c78f9d3cc11064e92dbd27a55235b86ceb25

Import glossary from openstack-manuals

import from openstack-manuals, just the path to the entities file
has been adjusted.

Hi Nikunj. Just something I wanted to bring up while you are working on this. This might fix the session timeout message on redirect to login page but I want to make sure it will also handle the case where there are unnecessary messages when the user explicitly logs out. Consider this scenario:

1) User changes password and is redirected to login page
2) Login page displays message "Password changed. Please log in again to continue."
3) User logs in again but explicitly logs out within 30 seconds
4) Login page still shows the message "Password changed. Please log in again to continue."

I think it would be great if this fix could handle all cases where there are unnecessary logout messages on the login page. Maybe that is your intention but it isn't clear from the commit message. Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 9647, 'date': '2014-07-30 17:32:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Also, I could be wrong but I think the logout_reason cookie is something that is part of horizon, not openstack_auth. So it seems a little wrong to me that we would add this kind of fix into openstack_auth.

FWIW, I took your fix described here (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/100855/) and made some slight changes that seem to fix the explicit logout issue I mentioned above. I'm not trying to butt in on your work, just thought it might give you some ideas. I did not try it with the session expiration scenario. Maybe something like this could work in all cases?

@vary.vary_on_cookie
def splash(request):
    if request.user.is_authenticated():
        response = shortcuts.redirect(horizon.get_user_home(request.user))
    else:
        form = forms.Login(request)
        request.session.clear()
        request.session.set_test_cookie()
        response = shortcuts.render(request, 'splash.html', {'form': form})
    response.delete_cookie('logout_reason')
    return response"}, {'account_id': 11599, 'date': '2014-07-30 17:55:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Justin: Thank You for all the comments and taking time to look into my patch.

Also the code You mentioned the Your second comment, i already submitted that also into another patch.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/100855

Please take a look into above patch also.'}, {'account_id': 11599, 'date': '2014-08-01 10:07:15.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

commit_message:
Fixes session timeout string in horizon

This bug fixes the session timeout string problem which
occurs when users clicks on the UI and Ui redirects the
user to the login page but without session timeout message.

Change-Id: Ifc7fa3cabca8092c7b3dd7bff3d0f526103ccdbb
Closes-Bug: #1231355

That said, backporting new configuration options is a giant red flag that something is feature-y (which is explicitly forbidden by stable maintenance guidelines), so I'm only +1'ing to express support for this one (also because I'm attributed as a Co-Author, as a result of helping to get this landed in master).'}, {'account_id': 1091, 'date': '2014-07-23 17:46:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2014-07-24 05:48:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

Not sure why would someone turn off referral chasing. But sure, I am all for flexibility.'}, {'account_id': 11387, 'date': '2014-07-24 06:12:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-07-24 20:37:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

Based on conversations in IRC, it appears havana is in security maintenance only. This would not be a security fix, and therefore inappropriate for havana.

commit_message:
Ability to turn off ldap referral chasing

When getting an ldap connection, check a config property to see if
referral chasing should be turned off.


Backport of 9c15b73f8361ce8606a531b5765c94b3927d99c4  with modifications

Co-Authored-By: Dolph Mathews <dolph.mathews@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I3bb5cc11b3c5c9108cfa656d5f5de1eaeb103fe5
Closes-Bug: 1233365

commit_message:
Add db model and api for worker

The db model is called 'Worker', it's used to store the rally worker
service status. And the following db apis are added:
 * register_worker
 * get_worker
 * unregister_worker
 * update_worker

Change-Id: I38c792cc133dbace10eb7f2d4d202ca05ec7f9cc

commit_message:
Compare Fuel versions as well as MOS ones

* Add rspec test cases for tricky and usual version formats, e.g.
  tricky: '2014.1.fuel5.0-mira4' vs '2014.1.1.fuel5.1-mira0'
  usual: '2014.1.fuel5.0-mira4' vs '2014.1.fuel5.1-mira0'
  (both for downgrading and installing cases)
* Make a yum downgrade decision based BOTH onto MOS versions and
  Fuel versions comparsion results instead of full MOSt versions
  ('fuel' hardcoded as a separator for MOS and Fuel versions in MOSt)

Closes-bug: #1342041

Change-Id: Icacec5ed01510ab526a4b0e6092efdf203a6a2cb
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Skip ostf tests if available image is absent

Need to skip heat "test_autoscaling" platform test and sahara
"test_platform_savanna" test if available images are absent.
(Now tests are fail in these cases.)

Change-Id: I28d037b11902dfa422893b588a689df75cd644b3
Closes-Bug: #1349390

commit_message:
Update glossary meta data

For syncing the glossary between repositories, let's use the same xml:id
everywhere. Let's use openstack_glossary here as this is the name used
in the OPS guide.

Also, use the content about updating the glossary that is used in the
OPS guide and improve it a bit.

implements bp common-glossary-setup

Change-Id: Icf070873b49c28ba3703e9443b69ae6515b63a1f

commit_message:
Make quotas APIv2 extension use Quotas object for create/update

This makes the quotas extension use the Quotas object for the
create/update operations instead of direct database access.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects-juno

Change-Id: Ia2db239d721c9ea680e11409e5eefc59e0dee941

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but python-neutronclient unittests don't

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but python-neutronclient unittests don't
currently pass with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Change-Id: I66c2c92e3b3d17448c8697f7607db7e6814abe14

commit_message:
Do not log 14+ INFO lines on a broken pipe error (eventlet)

Under eventlet if the client disconnects while Keystone is trying
to transmit data, approximately 14 lines of traceback are logged.

This could result in massive logs if done repeatedly; worst case
scenario could include a denial of service due to disk space being
exhausted.

Change-Id: Iaf14c64799daa7539d1bd85cb6c6457380c111d9
Closes-Bug: #1334466

commit_message:
Action-aware software config specification

Heat resources have a well-defined lifecycle, handling the lifecycle
actions CREATE, DELETE, SUSPEND, RESUME and UPDATE. Software components
in a Heat template should follow the same lifecycle-awareness and allow
for users to provide configuration hooks for the aforementioned actions.

Change-Id: If3f12a049719cdce31e98ece17ec3c482141972b

[{'created': '2014-07-30 13:26:27.000000000', 'message': 'Allow one-line if statements in check E011

At the moment the check E011 raises an issue when using
one-line if statements.

E011: Then keyword is not on same line as if keyword:
'    if [ ! "${SCRIPT:0:1}" = '/' ]; then SCRIPT=$PWD/$SCRIPT; fi'

Change-Id: I8d33d344db745c403f38d21f4cc472505b703370
'}]
commit_message:
Allow one-line if statements in check E011

At the moment the check E011 raises an issue when using
one-line if statements.

E011: Then keyword is not on same line as if keyword:
'    if [ ! "${SCRIPT:0:1}" = '/' ]; then SCRIPT=$PWD/$SCRIPT; fi'

Change-Id: I8d33d344db745c403f38d21f4cc472505b703370

All controller nodes are added into the list of swift devices and into
the list of memcache servers. This patch also removes swift storage nodes
from the list of memcache servers - I don't think that each storage node

Change-Id: Idb2ce2e2050fb84d8f8b564626b20e7b059fd685
"}]
commit_message:
Fix swift memcache and device properties

All controller nodes are added into the list of swift devices and into
the list of memcache servers. This patch also removes swift storage nodes
from the list of memcache servers - I don't think that each storage node
should run proxy server (also swift-storage element doesn't depend on
swift-proxy).

Change-Id: Idb2ce2e2050fb84d8f8b564626b20e7b059fd685

Updated to reflect latest development discovery. 

Santiago found that the AggregateInstanceExtraSpecsFilter requires a prefix of aggregate_instance_extra_specs to be used on flavors, but not on the aggregate itself.

I found another case where flavor has a different prefix (aka namespace or scope).  Basically, the desired virtual CPU topology can be set on both images and flavors via metadata. This is different from the Compute Capabilities filter as this is the virtual topology for the guest, not the host.  

The keys have different prefixes on images than on flavors. On flavors, keys are prefixed with “hw:”, but on images they are prefixed with hw_. I believe that this has to do with the Glance API not being able to handle semi-colons in the API (it uses headers which causes problems with “:”).

So, when a resource type is associated with a namespace, we need to allow for a custom prefix to be used.  In the event that the same base namespace may be used on a resource multiple times with different prefixes, we allow there to be multiple available prefixes. This may not be the case now, but the concern is that if another filter is added to nova that it may use a new scoping prefix and the users will need to choose which prefix to use when applying the metadata to the target resource (e.g. flavor).'}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2014-07-17 23:45:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-17 23:45:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Updated based on discussions from Glance mini-summit.  Summary:

There were a couple API patterns that we wanted better usability.

Don't use "detail" in URL itself. 

Don’t require deleting namespace contents in order to delete a namespace

Defer sort parameters until subsequent spec / commit (sort_key, sort_dir)

Defer project membership to a later commit. Initial commit to only handle visibility (public and private) and protected.  

In resource type association, change "metadata type" to "properties_target"

Need to add links to self and pagination to examples.

Don't use "metadata" as base for URL.  Too broad. (potentially more discussion needed).

For initial namespaces (aka. data seeding):

Do not put in db sync. Go directly as a command available from glance-manage.  

Make sure that devstack installs the definitions by default.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-29 00:51:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Verified+1

commit_message:
Metadata Definitions Catalog

A common API hosted by the Glance service for vendors, admins,
services, and users to meaningfully define available key / value
pair and tag metadata. The intent is to enable better metadata
collaboration across artifacts,services, and projects for
OpenStack users.

This is about the definition of the available metadata that can
be used on different types of resources (images, artifacts,
volumes, flavors, aggregates, etc). A definition includes the
properties type, its key, it's description, and it's constraints.
This catalog will not store the values for specific instance
properties.

Co-Authored-By: Travis Tripp <travis.tripp@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Lakshmi N Sampath <lakshmi.sampath@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: murali sundar <murali.sundar@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Wayne Okuma <wayne.okuma@hp.com>

Change-Id: I03219cf5168d9c22d07aa38653f8a9fb7ea380b8

commit_message:
Allow state specific *default* on_enter and on_exit

Instead of just supporting transition specific on_enter
and on_exit allow the state itself to provide a default
on_enter and on_exit that will be used when no transition
specific ones are provided. This allows for having (state,
transition) specific ones when needed/desired and having
state specific default ones when transition specific ones
are not provided.

Change-Id: If93b2c5b6be7e56c7c1fa0bed048401a2e3e7d00

commit_message:
Make quotas APIv3 extension use Quotas object for create/update

This makes the quotas extension use the Quotas object for the
create/update operations instead of direct database access.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects-juno

Change-Id: I74295a6f8ebca46421eafedbb28e677d2361c2b8

commit_message:
Update pep8 testing

Remove comment about H904 since H904 has been removed from hacking,
there's no need to fix it.
Remove E712 ignore since the code is clean.
Remove E711 ignore and fix the problems in manila/db/sqlalchemy/api.py to
make it pass.
Remove H304 ignore since the code is clean.

Change-Id: I4f9477a61d6f1ddde16b5ff9e387c76076c89d6e

commit_message:
Add quota limit create/update methods to Quotas object

This adds two methods to the Quotas object that are effectively
passthroughs to the DB api calls. Since the Quotas object isn't
actually a representation of what is in the database, and because
we've (incorrectly) got some logic in the DB API around how the
quotas are applied, this is just a temporary step. Ideally, we
would (will) refactor Quotas in several ways in the near future,
at which time the way all of this works can be revisited and
cleaned up.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects-juno

Change-Id: If93614cd27e56667e0f106e8045dd1adc633ff1b

commit_message:
Add proxy support to dynect client

Note that it is not possible to reference $http_proxy as a default to http_proxy. See https://github.com/openstack/oslo.config/blob/master/oslo/config/cfg.py#L218-L244 for more info.

Change-Id: I67ae37c74975a292d35c8a990fb4e43cd5e69d07
Closes-Bug: #1348296

commit_message:
merge.py --hot to process and generate HOT

This adds a --hot flag to merge.py which will assume source templates
are in the HOT format, and generate a HOT template artifact.

Tests have also been ported to HOT, along with some minor corrections
to the existing tests to make the source and result templates valid
heat templates.

Partial-Blueprint: tripleo-juno-remove-mergepy

Change-Id: If18ff79f89456123c884a1ab2f910ce4cc9a6e0b

'}, {'created': '2014-07-17 10:34:39.000000000', 'message': 'Create marconi queue when infra stack is created

* We need to create a marconi queue in Solum so the solum-infra-guestagent
can consume jobs and orchestrate tools of the infra like drone, jenkins
or gitolite.
* Added a unique identifier as name of the marconi queue: {infra_stack_id}

commit_message:
Create marconi queue when infra stack is created

* We need to create a marconi queue in Solum so the solum-infra-guestagent
can consume jobs and orchestrate tools of the infra like drone, jenkins
or gitolite.
* Added a unique identifier as name of the marconi queue: {infra_stack_id}

Change-Id: Iaeb3fa7f4a1885eaa28677e1eb7f1b46126623e3
Co-Authored-By: Pierre Padrixe <pierre.padrixe@numergy.com>
Partially-Implements: bp/solum-git-push
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/solum/+spec/solum-git-push

[{'created': '2014-07-18 19:26:56.000000000', 'message': 'Adds and cleans up undocumented policies in policy.json

Some policies for specific actions exist in Manila but are not documented in
etc/manila/policy.json. This makes someone have to dig to see what is available
when looking quickly.

The fix adds all actions from the APIs to policy.json, with default policy for
the newly added actions. The fix also removes two actions no longer in the API
(quotas:update_for_user and quotas:update_for_project) and replaces them with
quotas:update using the same rule (admin_or_projectadmin). The rule definition
for admin_or_projectadmin is also added to policy.json.

Change-Id: I2e9510d59d0d3b70974f1a851ee5d2246154caf4
Closes-Bug: #1326797

commit_message:
Adds undocumented policies and defaults in policy.json

Some policies for specific actions exist in Manila but are not documented in
etc/manila/policy.json. This makes someone have to dig to see what is available
when looking quickly.

The fix adds all actions from the APIs to policy.json, with default policy for
most of the newly added actions, and rule:admin_api for the rest. The fix
changes the share_network and security_service actions to default. The fix also
removes four actions no longer in the API. The actions quotas:update_for_user
and quotas:update_for_project are replaced with quotas:update. The actions
share_network:activate and share:network:deactivate have been removed.

Change-Id: I2e9510d59d0d3b70974f1a851ee5d2246154caf4
Closes-Bug: #1326797

commit_message:
Add check on eventlet bug #105 (ipv6 support)

If our environment contain package dnspython and have ipv6 enabled in
the system, we have a problem. We have a couple of tests that
fail in such environment.

Add utils.is_eventlet_bug105 function to test environment on this
issue. Also add utils.is_ipv6_configured(moved from tests
.test_wsgi.TestWSGIServer._ipv6_configured).

Add additional constraints to ipv6 tests.

Quick workaround for problem - set environment variable
EVENTLET_NO_GREENDNS.

Change-Id: I9e91ffcca225a556842e97db07dbb0edaddf8393

commit_message:
Prevent python 2.7 from being purged in container

Python 2.7 is being removed, somehow, despite python3 being specified.
This should fix the issue and make the container usable again.

Change-Id: Ida8aa7e527f8230cc893adf9192003340fc0dbf5

Change-Id: I0549b8ca9ba41b734277600cb66a74b27ca72d88

(cherry picked from commit e0638e29cda39c609ecf518e5adacf70e158d71a)

commit_message:
VMware: prevent image snapshot if no root disk defined

If there is no root disk defined then the snapshot should
throw an exception.

Change-Id: I0549b8ca9ba41b734277600cb66a74b27ca72d88
Related-bug: #1297605
(cherry picked from commit e0638e29cda39c609ecf518e5adacf70e158d71a)

commit_message:
WIP: Correct /var/run SELinux file contexts

/var/run/keystone and /var/run/nova also need to be relabeled
with the correct file contexts. These directories are created
anew each boot.

Change-Id: I500604d92d20e7b5be4b27a37050bb4cf474db4e

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

Hi Murali,

See my comment inline. I would prefer that you create a specific scheduler for the dvr purpose so that you could leverage some others. There were some discussions about leveraging the VRRP bp for the service node. I introduced a scheduler for the VRRP purpose https://review.openstack.org/66347. 
Maybe you could build your scheduler on top of it in order to use it when scheduling a router on the service nodes ?

Add L3 Scheduler Changes for Distributed Routers

This patch implements the L3 Scheduler changes for the
Distributed Virtual Routers.

Partially-implements: blueprint neutron-ovs-dvr
