(1 comment)

Overall, I'm warming up to having plugins manage transport keys, partly because I found out that uniqueness constraints in mysql are limited in size out of the box. So overall getting a transport key ID from the plugin (so having plugin CRUD the key), storing that id along with the plugin name in barbican core, and then having a means to retrieve the key and giving back to client for their transport/wrapping. Make sense.

Plugins do need to be careful not to assume the key is only in memory due to the multiple API case though, but if the source of truth for the actual key is a system separate from Barbican API nodes, shouldn't be a problem."}, {'account_id': 9914, 'date': '2014-07-25 18:56:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-25 18:56:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
code to retrieve transport key on metadata request

When creating secret metadata, if transport key wrapping is required,
then select a plugin that supports key wrapping, and return the
transport_key_ref.

Implements: blueprint add-wrapping-key-to-barbican-server
Change-Id: I60c546655abcaf3f39bb88d541bb9d03f95d3556

commit_message:
py3.x: Use six.text_type() instead of unicode()

Python 3 doesn't support unicode(), use six.text_type instead.
Partial-Bug: #1284677
Partially-implements blueprint py3-compatibility

Change-Id: I5f66ce70e838fedc955f5284c3c480bc37420107

commit_message:
Remove reference to 'in-use' state in share manager

State 'in-use' is leftover from Cinder and is not used by shares,
hence it should be removed.
Due to absense of tests for this module at all, as part of bug fix
were added unittests.

Change-Id: I768d731bac3eb1f420695082e69598e55e1de90b
Closes-Bug: #1346371
Partial-Bug: #1348635

commit_message:
Use oslo.rootwrap library instead of local copy

Remove rootwrap code copied from oslo-incubator, make
manila-rootwrap a console_script entrypoint pointing in
oslo.rootwrap instead.

Partially-implements blueprint use-common-code

Change-Id: I519e8dec24dc9c48243af41dc0f423c05a0d92e2

commit_message:
py3: use six.string_types instead of basestring

six is the canonical compatibility library for supporting Python 2 and 3
in a single codebase.

The basestring was removed in Python 3 and we should use 'six.string_types'
instead of 'basestring' to make code compatible with py 2 and 3 as well.

Partially-implements blueprint py3-compatibility

Change-Id: Idb452afdc2a828089627e14f90c53f3967ceb2ad

[{'created': '2014-06-01 18:14:22.000000000', 'message': 'Make linux.utils.execute log error on return codes

Previously, the execute method in neutron logs everything as debug which hides
a lot of extremely fatal errors like unable to apply security group rules!
This patch changes this code so that we log all non 0 returns as error.

Change-Id: I7328e62269212ccd9c7950ff064a3e337de56918
Closes-bug: 1323832
Related-bug: 1322945
(cherry picked from commit 77046d0d889a8bff095083ae80a2accd0e25406b)
'}]
commit_message:
Make linux.utils.execute log error on return codes

Previously, the execute method in neutron logs everything as debug which hides
a lot of extremely fatal errors like unable to apply security group rules!
This patch changes this code so that we log all non 0 returns as error.

Change-Id: I7328e62269212ccd9c7950ff064a3e337de56918
Closes-bug: 1323832
Related-bug: 1322945
(cherry picked from commit 77046d0d889a8bff095083ae80a2accd0e25406b)

commit_message:
Add new option to the 'list' shell command

Manila API that is used by 'list' command is going to support
new key 'share_server_id'.

Partially implements bp add-admin-api-list-shares-for-share-server

Change-Id: I70822d2e6bfc16b8407f3bf917119dcb9a551bf0

commit_message:
Includes a basic HOT template guide

The 2 RST files are copied from the heat developer documentation without
any change and are just a starting point.

This patch requires this change in the openstack-doc-tools:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/108034/

Change-Id: I03511655c86ead880cadfa68b43bb2b90d3f7c06
Implements: blueprint heat-templates

commit_message:
Sort security group rules by protocol and port

When adding new rules to a security group, it is useful to have the
rules sorted consistently across page reloads. This patch ensures
that the rules are sorted by protocol first, then by port. It is still
possible to manually sort the table using the client side capabilities,
but by default the table is now sorted by protocol and port, server
side.

Change-Id: I36d29461a8437f5689425706a7faae3399c6bf23
Closes-bug: #1326132
(cherry picked from commit e8c1f60eae7e3a76fd271dd5f14c80d06dfe6ebd)

This doesn't make sense to me: can't we provide an appropriate SELinux policy on Fedora? If the Swift server ports are wrong, this should be fixed upstream (or even with IANA). Making this a parameter to the overall deployment feels very wrong given that this is all discoverable via keystone.

To be clear, my objection here is not about the port #, its about the UI implications of making this internal detail a user level parameter, and of the breaking of upstream choices."}, {'account_id': 7471, 'date': '2014-07-11 04:17:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@lifeless, upstream swift prefers not to move the default port numbers because they can be changed in the configuration files if desired.

I've been coordinating with the SELinux and RDO folks and we decided to change the swift port numbers for RDO packages from 6000-6002 to 6201-6203 in the packaged configuration files. We couldn't use 6000 because it conflicts with xserver. The selinux policy change has already been pushed to Fedora updates. The change to the swift packages are still flowing through.

This change along with the heat template change provides a way for those who use the swift packages to use the ports that are allowed by the updated SELinux policy package."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-14 15:08:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Make swift server ports configurable

Allows the default swift object, container, and account ports to
be changed through heat.

The default ports need to be changed for Fedora based
distributions because the SELinux policy expects the ports to be
6201 for object server, 6202 for container server, and 6203
for account server.

See https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1112823

Change-Id: Id27034a641dbc27a88b70da47b0353be4694819c

commit_message:
Ability to change default swift ports

The configuration and os-refresh-config scripts have been updated
to allow the swift ports to be changed through heat metadata.

This change is needed by Fedora based distributions running in SELinux
enforcing mode.  The SELinux policies allow swift to bind to ports
6201-6203 which is different from the default 6000-6002. The reason
the policies could not be updated to allow ports 6000-6002, is because
that range overlaps with xserver.

See https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1112823

Related to Id27034a641dbc27a88b70da47b0353be4694819c

Change-Id: I44404eff352e0527e7d0d01493a7b1b7ce4a52e5

commit_message:
Moved datasource module registry

Previously the datasource module registry was stored in
congress/tests/snapshot.

This change moves it to a proper location:
congress/server/snapshot.

Change-Id: Ic25b4b982cbe5ac44608189fa9bdee666ec91828

commit_message:
Port iBoot PDU driver from Nova

Ports a custom power driver from Nova to Ironic so that iBoot capable
devices can be used.

Co-Authored-By: Dan Prince <dprince@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1226042
Change-Id: Ibec34a7e0a69bb26d3e2a21b1f2d1a7ce3514347

commit_message:
Hyper-v: Change the hyper-v error log for debug when resize failed

The error message is not sufficient enough for debug of hyper-v
when resize error occured, this patch adding the necessary info
in error log.

Closes-bug: #1238430
(cherry-picked from commit 6ee68137c5ea9af99c1db4e2a2ce555f43a9e3e1)

Change-Id: Ic8ecb8f08139face2c7bdca258de5e719d81833c

commit_message:
Remove unneeded definitions of Python Source Code Encoding

PEP 0263 (http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0263/) is not
used anywhere else and should be removed when it's not needed.

Change-Id: I1e92c2c2c99090d174a9f61b3782d63de6175e4d

commit_message:
Attach/detach interface to paused instance with affect live flag

Currently attach/detach interface to paused instance is only with
VIR_DOMAIN_AFFECT_CONFIG flags. After instance unpause, there isn't
any effect on the instance, unless restart the instance. So add
flag VIR_DOMAIN_AFFECT_LIVE when attach/detach interface.

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/virt/libvirt/test_libvirt.py

Change-Id: Iedfc7f6fc06e72d8e3eecebede1274582c8043fd
Closes-Bug: #1299331

commit_message:
Do not pass instances without host to compute API

Even if the server external events extension filters out events
whose related instance does not have a host, the corresponding
instance is still sent to the compute API module.
As this might result in KeyError, instance without host should
be filtered out before calling the compute API module.

Change-Id: If5229ec3059076dbc9f4abb6625504e8864c265e
Closes-Bug: #1348584
(cherry picked from commit 5e4a5f0d8c62ca6e94ae6db16e9fbe0428805158)

commit_message:
Do not process events for instances without host

In some cases Neutron might send events such as 'VIF unplugged'
for instances which are either being deleted or shelved. When
that happens there will be a failure in dispatching the event
to the appropriate compute node - as there is no host for the
instance.

As multiple neutron events can be stashed in a single call
it is important to avoid that this kind of errors will prevent
processing of other events in the same call.

This patch does not process events for instances without a host,
marking them as failed.

When the above condition occurs, the create event request will
return a 207 response code. For specific events, a 422
unprocessable entity code will be set.

This patch also preserve the characteristic that events are
returned in the response in the same order they were found in
the request.

Change-Id: I18062b81e50c722ec96b4296ac39384493683ae3
Closes-Bug: #1333654
(cherry picked from commit 4f8ccd7b95c27180a1cfe689e3c6f46bde5f803b)

commit_message:
Disable broken unit test (related to "Change Password")

The new django_openstack_auth 1.1.6 library surfaced a defect in this
test, whereby the test client does not properly log out the user. This
only affects the test, the functionality otherwise works fine.

This temporarily disables the test in order to repair the gate, while
waiting to replace it with a new unit test more reduced in scope and/or
an integration test.

Change-Id: I8779666c053a4835e22038a39a530fe5fc84b6a3
Closes-Bug: #1333144
(cherry picked from commit 5455b8f6f595633513b6521449ebc1985d5b9070)

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but ceilometer unittests don't currently
pass with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Change-Id: Ibc613d77ad52d5f7d8d613f3dd66ffba4117ff72
(cherry picked from commit 860a2852ca92df20fa886cec2e75d753ac6e18bb)

commit_message:
Avoid AttributeError: SecurityGroup error handle

On the project/access_and_security/security_groups/<detail> page, some
errors inside the
openstack_dashboard/dashboards/
project/access_and_security/security_groups/views
DetailView._get_data method are still resulting in a None being
returned. This causes an error in the DetailView.get_data method as
NoneTypes clearly don't have a .rules attribute.

I'm not sure why the error is sneaking through the exceptions.handle
above, but they most definitely are. Perhaps Ana Krivokapic's changes
here: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/84109/ may eventually solve this,
but it's unclear.

In the mean time, and potentially correct overall, if a None is
returned, the get_data method should return an empty list instead of
throwing an exception.

Change-Id: Ibc3bbb8c1302fca0c8a134abee8b7c649ad8c315
Closes-Bug: 1312192
(cherry picked from commit d8bafff484b6ed264af913af3709e61976bc2177)

commit_message:
Fix security group modal header overflow

If you go to Edit Instance > Security Group
The two headers "All Security Groups" and "Instance Security Groups"
overflow when translated

commit_message:
Add strict dependencies to the overcloud template

Currently there is very weak (no) ordering of StructuredDeployments during
heat stack creation (and, importantly, update) on the overcloud. This can
cause the deployment which sends the completion signal back to Heat to
happen before all others have completed, which in turn leads Heat to state
the stack is ready while ORC is still configuring services

The only workaround to this is to wait an unknown amount of time after the
heat stack completes before the system is usable.

This patch prevents the completion signal from being returned early, by
ensuring these are strictly ordered:
    controller0Deploy
    controller0Passthrough
    controller0AllNodesDeploy
    NovaCompute0Deploy
    NovaCompute0Passthrough
    NovaCompute0AllNodesDeploy

Change-Id: I0a549370b7aca55b1145de521ad51218428deaf5

Correct overcloud template to inherit passthrough

Inherit passthrough from nova-compute-instance.yaml, rather than
having an exact copy in overcloud-source.yaml.

Change-Id: I4f5a4a7be5835cb68755734aa72f8d9670cba0d4

commit_message:
Rename NovaCompute0Config to NovaCompute0Deploy

Rename NovaCompute0Config to NovaCompute0Deploy as this makes
the structured deployment name match the one in
nova-compute-instance.yaml.

new sample keystone.conf from the keystone repo (which doesn't contain
this problem anymore).

commit_message:
Mechanism to cleanup all ImageCaches

This spec talks about creating a mechanism to cleanup all the image
caches (leveraging most of the code that is already in pxe driver).

Change-Id: I7608cf327bb40ff6bac53ee527cd42704888a5e8

- check-rally-dsvm-glance http://logs.openstack.org/85/94485/1/check/check-rally-dsvm-glance/5bede09 : SUCCESS in 30m 18s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2014-05-21 09:04:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Does the 'download_image' policy cover your use case? Or do you need to selectively allow/disallow image download on an image by image case?"}, {'account_id': 9303, 'date': '2014-05-21 16:05:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Stuart,

We are selectively allow/disallow image download on an image by image case.
For this we are using protected property for restriction.
Administrator can configure this policy as per requirement.'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2014-05-21 16:23:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Abishek,

Ok, that makes sense, and I think allowing download on a per image basis is a valid thing to do.

That being said, this feels like using protected properties in a way that wasn't initially envisaged. Protected properties were designed to allow the protection of meta-data values themselves, eg to set a license property that couldn't be tampered with by the user, rather than data operations.

I'm not sure what the alternative is at this point in time.

There was some discussion at the summit about 'composite tokens'. They could
conceivably help here by providing a way to differentiate requests which have come from nova compute (a composite token could be created by nova compute and contain a nova compute role, which would not be present in a request which had come directly from a user.)
Combining a composite token with a new core property 'is_downloadable' which would be enforced against the nova compute role could help here, and potentially in other similar cases.

I'd be interested to hear markwash's thoughts."}, {'account_id': 616, 'date': '2014-05-27 16:39:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I think there needs to be a way to add this restriction to policy rather than property protections. As Stuart said, property protections are ways to protect a specific property, not the image itself.

I think it should be possible with some modification or update to policy checking to add a rule like.

"rule:restricted": "not True:target.some_image_property"

and then say
"download_image": "role:admin or rule:restricted"

which would result in images that have "some_image_property" set to True to  not be downloadable by regular users.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-27 16:39:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Starting check jobs.

[{'created': '2014-05-20 21:58:39.000000000', 'message': 'Restrict users from downloading protected image

Added download operation to the protected properties.

For example,
[^x_billing_code_ntt_xyz.*]
create = admin,owner
read = admin,Member,_member_
update = admin,owner
delete = admin,owner
download= admin,owner

Currently, property protection is defined only for Create, Read, Update
and Delete (CRUD) operations. In addition to this Download operation need
to be added in order to restrict downloading image having protected
properties.

Modified v1 and v2 api to add download restriction.
Modified logic of caching to restrict download for v1 and v2 api.

To use this feature, intended user need to deploy two glance-api services
with common glanc registry and backend.
One api would be specific to nova where user will configure policy to allow
any user to download the image whereas in another set, it will restrict user
from downloading the image if you have enabled protected properties policy.

DocImpact: Need to modify following options in glance-api.conf file to enable
property-protections:

property_protection_file = property-protections-roles.conf
property_protection_rule_format = roles

Deployer need to create or modify "property-protections-roles.conf" as per
requirement to define accessible roles for protected property.

Change-Id: I4e10871832eb84ef91c3585ef8f7b61f38040b53
blueprint: restrict-downloading-images-protected-properties

commit_message:
Restrict users from downloading protected image

Added download operation to the protected properties.

For example,
[^x_billing_code_ntt_xyz.*]
create = admin,owner
read = admin,Member,_member_
update = admin,owner
delete = admin,owner
download= admin,owner

Currently, property protection is defined only for Create, Read, Update
and Delete (CRUD) operations. In addition to this Download operation need
to be added in order to restrict downloading image having protected
properties.

Modified v1 and v2 api to add download restriction.
Modified logic of caching to restrict download for v1 and v2 api.

To use this feature, intended user need to deploy two glance-api services
with common glanc registry and backend.
One api would be specific to nova where user will configure policy to allow
any user to download the image whereas in another set, it will restrict user
from downloading the image if you have enabled protected properties policy.

DocImpact: Need to modify following options in glance-api.conf file to enable
property-protections:

property_protection_file = property-protections-roles.conf
property_protection_rule_format = roles

Deployer need to create or modify "property-protections-roles.conf" as per
requirement to define accessible roles for protected property.

Change-Id: I4e10871832eb84ef91c3585ef8f7b61f38040b53
blueprint: restrict-downloading-images-protected-properties

commit_message:
Implement AWS "Updates are not supported"

Ability to completely deny an update to a resource's property
is present in AWS but is missing from Heat.

Change-Id: I3d12104fbd96ec09a284f56de7c80df67e527372

commit_message:
cinder-type: delete PATH in exec

By deleting PATH, we are able to run both commands (cinder type-* and
grep) without environment issue.

Change-Id: I5dd1c60892c7848b02ab71ea30bc49b4b4c26029
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

If quota on ports are disabled in neutron (see below), neutronv2 api
set port quota to None and quota check raises a TypeError.

  [quotas]
  quota_items=network,subnet,router,floatingip

commit_message:
Neutronv2 api does not support neutron without port quota

If quota on ports are disabled in neutron (see below), neutronv2 api
set port quota to None and quota check raises a TypeError.

  # neutron server /etc/neutron/neutron.conf
  [quotas]
  quota_items=network,subnet,router,floatingip

This change set port quota to -1 (unlimited) if quota on ports are
disabled.

Change-Id: I89c530dd57a7beb35695be124ca8511148378458
Closes-Bug: #1333315
(cherry picked from commit 04add2ed0d8b0341ea347ac98834f75cf5b2be1d)

hi cedric

the nova spec seems missed their SPD too.'}, {'account_id': 6772, 'date': '2014-07-18 14:48:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The Nova proposal made the SPD for Nova but was not approved by the SAD deadline, I believe Sean has proposed it for an exception on the mailing list.
 
Obviously an exception in the SPD for Neutron would still be required for the Neutron side of the feature to be considered for Juno.'}, {'account_id': 11604, 'date': '2014-07-19 21:59:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

this feature was originally intended as a nova only change.
the original implementation which was developed during the icehouse cycle used a configuration option in nova to specify if the compute node required dpdkvhost.

based on feedback from the nova spec we created this neutron spec to propose an auto detect mechanism which will allow neutron to tell nova if the selected compute node requires/supports dpdk userspace vhost.

once the neutron spec approval deadline passes tomorrow we will ask for an exception as we have for nova.

if both exceptions are granted i will work to iterate the specs to incorporate feedback before the end of the exception period.hopefully we can progress them to a mergeable/approvable state for inclusion in the juno cycle.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-21 17:18:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Use keystone.host in stackrc

/root/stackrc has a hardcoded value of localhost for OS_AUTH_URL,
which doesn't help when we can't talk to it due to VIP changes. Set
it to keystone.host.

Change-Id: If952f383e8970e3298c36cdd750f6c6a20209e81

subject: Support dpdkvhost in LibvirtGenericVIFDriver

Przemyslaw Czesnowicz please connect with Luke Gorrie to work together on writing a single spec for support of vhost user feature. It doesn't make sense to have two specs ( https://review.openstack.org/#/c/96138/ )for essentially the same feature, and I don't want to arbitrarily pick one to approve & one to reject myself - much better if you can resolve it between yourselves."}, {'account_id': 7916, 'date': '2014-07-03 09:48:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

I would like to clarify that the two "userspace vhost" specifications for Juno are based on completely different implementations.

This specification is based on the DPDK implementation of userspace vhost that uses a plain tap device in QEMU and then replaces /dev/vhost-net with a FUSE device to intercept the vhost protocol. Details are here: https://github.com/01org/dpdk-ovs/blob/master/docs/04_Sample_Configurations/03_Userspace-vHost.md

The other specification (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/96138/) is based on the new QEMU vhost-user feature.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-07-03 09:56:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the clarification Luke.

Przemyslaw can you update this spec so that it avoids referring to 'vhost userspace' as that is leading to significant confusion with QEMU's built-in 'vhost-user' network device type.

I'd suggest refering to this as 'vhost fuse' to reflect its implementation. eg we could use VIF_VHOSTFUSE as the VIF type in neutron / nova."}, {'account_id': 11604, 'date': '2014-07-03 14:03:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

hello daniel
two other points i should probably clarify.
Przemyslaw is the tech-lead of the team i work on. he is currently on vacation so i will be working on this feature on his behalf until he returns in 2/3 weeks.

the usecase we are targeting is also quite different then the one that luke is trying to enable. the userspace vhost implementation provided in dpdk has been integrated into intels accelerated openvswitch and patches to enable it in standard openvswitch have also been submitted.

with this implementation we are explicitly trying to support qemu versions less than 2.0 with both openvswitch versions and enable this feature via both the openvswich mechanism driver and the open daylight mechanism driver.

as support for the qemu 2.1 vhost userspace backend will not be available in either openvswitch in the juno time frame luck's approach will not enable our usecase.

regarding the vif type perhaps VIF_DPDKVHOST is more appropriate as this is the name of the port_type in both switches.

i will update the spec document if i am able with more information to avoid further confusion.
regards
sean"}, {'account_id': 3217, 'date': '2014-07-04 00:20:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

hi i will update both the neutron and nova spec tomorrow based on the feedback in the comments. in addition to this i will propose my changes to the ovs-discuss mailing list and ask for feedback.  while i believe the ovs changes would simplify future detection mechanisms they are not required to enable this feature.

tomorrows changes:
1 i will update both specs to reflect that a new vif type will be created.
2 i will add the details of the detection mechanism to the neutron spec.
3 i will ask the ovs-discuss mailing list for feedback on the proposed changes to a future open vswitch. 
4 i will add a link to the references section of the neutron spec to the discussion thread on the ovs-discuss mailing list
5 add a note that supporting side by side deployments of any combination kernel open vswitch, dpdk enabled open vswitch and the intel(R) dpdk vswitch on the same compute node is out of scope of the current change.
6 update nova spec to use VIF_TYPE_VHOST_CUSE

while item 5 might be nice for some use cases the changes required to support this would be two large to complete in the juno cycle. if this use case is desired dpdkvhost could be extended in kilo. for Juno the same use case could be satisfied by having some node use standard ovs and other use dpdk enabled ovs. host aggregates could then be used to select the vswitch based on workloads.

regards

commit_message:
Support dpdkvhost in LibvirtGenericVIFDriver

Propose to extend LibvirtGenericVIFDriver class to support
dpdkvhost. This will allow Openvswitch derivatives that
use Intel(R) DPDK to be used with Openstack.

Blueprint: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/libvirt-ovs-use-usvhost

Change-Id: Ibcf7d5354e39fa3ad4d021acff8d3e3e50c0900d

commit_message:
VMware: use default values in get_info() when properties are missing

The properties that we retrieve from VirtualMachineConfigSummary are
optional ('summary.config.numCpu', 'summary.config.memorySizeMB') and
if they are missing we should return default values from get_info()

This patch also improves the unit test for get_info(). It removes the
test in test_driver_api.py (test_get_info() and test_spawn() are the
same) and adds a new test in test_vmops.py

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/virt/vmwareapi/test_driver_api.py
	nova/tests/virt/vmwareapi/test_vmops.py

Closes-Bug: 1317912
Change-Id: Ibbb28985d13de371fdac8a119ad820d25acc21be
(cherry picked from commit 2db7528ca258d7b0c1205ab2f9a76569d9f9a82d)

commit_message:
controller0AllNodesConfig to controller0AllNodes.

Rename all occurrences of controller0AllNodesConfig to
controller0AllNodes as this is in line with compute node
deployments. Also the current naming is confusing as this is a
deployment step not a configuration step.

Change-Id: I8efa3b6a64a099e1e8ee43009472152aed5f8ad8

Will keeping logs in /mnt/state complicate upgrade? I understand it's nice to have the (historic) logs preserved through an upgrade. For the proxy log, not loosing the logs in an upgrade is a pre-requisite for accurate billing. However, it means an upgrade might have to handle subsequent changes in log file layout.

OpenStack components generally use /var/log/blah. Can we have a symlink from /var/log/swift to /mnt/state/var/swift so users can find them?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-01 14:51:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Chris, thanks for the review comments.

Wrt swift logging to /mnt/state, I did this to preserve swift logs during upgrade. However, if this is not the normal/preferred place to log than I have no problem changing it to /var/log/swift.

Wrt logging to /var/log/upstart, the swift daemons do not log to stdout, but rather use python logging package, in particular the SysLogHandler to log everything to syslog. I believe swift is a little different to the other projects in this regard!

Wrt the empty elements/swift/install.d/75-swift-dirs, I'm not quite sure how that happened and will remove it.

So I propose changing my patch to have swift log to /var/log/swift rather than /mnt/state/var/log/swift. Do you think this will be acceptable?"}, {'account_id': 1253, 'date': '2014-05-21 15:24:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Actually it looks like a number of other services are creating a log dir in /mnt/state/var/log:

root@overcloud-controller0-uct6fqtza7eb:/mnt/state/var/log# ls -l /mnt/state/var/log/
total 20
drwxr-xr-x 2 glance   glance   4096 May 20 12:46 glance
drwxrwxr-x 2 root     mysql    4096 May 20 12:46 mysql
drwxrwxr-x 2 neutron  neutron  4096 May 20 12:46 neutron

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-05-01 09:04:55.000000000', 'message': 'Move swift logs from /var/log/syslog into their own log files

Swift uses syslog to handle all of its logging needs. By default swift
logs are added to /var/log/syslog. This can add quite a bit of clutter
to this log file and makes it more difficult to debug swift issues.

This change locates swift logs as follows:

/mnt/state/var/log/swift/proxy.log
    Contains all logs from proxy server
/mnt/state/var/log/swift/server.log
    Contains all logs from account, container & object servers
/mnt/state/var/log/swift/background.log
    Contains all logs from daemons such as replicators, auditors, updaters
    and reaper.

This change also enables proxy server logging i.e. add proxy-logging (x2) to
the proxy server pipeline and includes the proxy-logging filter to
proxy-server.conf.

This change also sets reveal_sensitive_prefix config option so only 18 chars
of the X-Auth-Token are displayed in the proxy server log messages to avoid
revealing this sensitive data and to avoid clutter in the log (X-Auth-Token is
large).

Change-Id: I80ce0ae002eb58b420bddc253ca186d2147c2000

commit_message:
Add proxy-logging to proxy-server pipeline

This change enables proxy server logging i.e. add proxy-logging
(x2) to the proxy server pipeline and includes the proxy-logging filter
to proxy-server.conf.

Change-Id: I80ce0ae002eb58b420bddc253ca186d2147c2000

commit_message:
Logging audit for trove/guestagent/backup module

Adjust logging to conform to logging standards.
Cleaned up some messages that were unclear. Also
corrected the usage of the word Backup which was
inconsistently capitalized in some messages.

Also addressed a pattern of exception handlers using
LOG.error merely to log the exception (instead of
using LOG.exception)

Change-Id: Id2eb57d3395273f9aebd41de0146f7a2fc2774c8
Partial-Bug: #1324206

If an instance has an empty security group list an exception
is thrown due to iteration attempt of None.

To fix this, this patch modifies get_instance_security_group

commit_message:
Fix security group list when not defined for an instance

If an instance has an empty security group list an exception
is thrown due to iteration attempt of None.

To fix this, this patch modifies get_instance_security_group
to return an empty list instead of None.

Change-Id: I7efb3c3a58d7e20501d126c6d194479ca1d14166
Closes-Bug: #1291489
(cherry picked from commit c32986966dfd034c3d706b2e9ab2820a2c3cfc3e)

commit_message:
OpenStack Security Guide - Chapter 35: Grammatical and Format errors

Dissolving multiple grammatical errors, inclusive of awkward wording and improper punctuation; recharging "SSL" with "SSL/TLS"

Change-Id: Ia07eba1901ee71dd81492ed9548f0485d2876427
Closes-Bug: #1342912

[{'created': '2014-06-19 22:08:02.000000000', 'message': 'Add support for os_region_name

For environments with multiple endpoints due to regions, tasks such as
cinder volume attach will not work unless os_region_name is set. This
allows the os_region_name to be passed in.

Change-Id: I5cc41385741054281dafb501742a0d7b26099f88
'}]
commit_message:
Add support for os_region_name

For environments with multiple endpoints due to regions, tasks such as
cinder volume attach will not work unless os_region_name is set. This
allows the os_region_name to be passed in.

Change-Id: I5cc41385741054281dafb501742a0d7b26099f88

commit_message:
Do not schedule network when creating reserved DHCP port

If device_id is DEVICE_ID_RESERVED_DHCP_PORT, do not schedule
network nor notify to dhcp-agent.

Closes-Bug: #1327000
Change-Id: Idf88767596bf0fc31bf856a423d35cb1575b57f3

get the extremely descriptive True != False when the test fails.

commit_message:
assertTrue/False should have msg param

assertTrue / False should really have a msg param. Otherwise we
get the extremely descriptive True != False when the test fails.
Some times, that's ok.

But in the base case it's not. This doesn't yet fix any of the
issues, but is posted for consideration about whether we think
this would be helpful.

Change-Id: Ib002564f54a0a6ae390a70908549fb5fc5a84372

commit_message:
Switch to Horizon 2014.2.b2

There was a change merged to Horizon master a few days ago that upgrades
Twitter Bootstrap from version 2.x to version 3.x. There are lots changes
in the version upgrade that affect both CSS and JS.

Change-Id: I856aa0b8eb5ee44acbed74a7f6a49a037321bf91

commit_message:
Include pending task in log message on skip sync_power_state

To better understand why sync_power_state is being skipped include the
pending task name in the log message.

Change-Id: I832a3d5820efab301e12610b28ca2a1e5cfd946a
(cherry picked from commit affbbca5af2506aafb743211c901f7f0ca4e131a)

commit_message:
versions API: ignore request with a body

Update the OS API versions controller so it ignores requests
with a body. Previously an incoming (unauthenticated)
request to the versions API would log a TypeError trace
in the nova-api.log file with the following message:

TypeError: index() got an unexpected keyword argument 'body'

Change-Id: Icc3ccfc537b13627b8d5ba43ae3ba91e34e08c9e
Closes-bug: #1306727

[{'created': '2014-06-05 21:19:17.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: Refresh volume connection_info after volume snapshot

The following patch is related to the guest assisted snapshot
functionality.  When you take a snapshot of a volume
(e.g. GlusterFS) attached to a running instance, a new snapshot
file is created, i.e. volume-<uuid>.<snapshot-uuid>.  The
instance uses this file as the active volume.  If you shutdown
and restart the instance, nova will reattach the base volume
(volume-<uuid>) to the instance instead of the snapshot volume
(volume-<uuid>.<snapshot-uuid>).  The expected behavior is to
have the snapshot volume reattach to the instance.  This is
caused by stale data being returned from the database when
_get_instance_volume_block_device_info is called during
_power_on.  To fix this bug, this patch calls
refresh_connection_info to update the database in both
volume_snapshot_create and _volume_snapshot_delete methods of the
libvirt driver.

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/virt/libvirt/test_libvirt.py

Change-Id: I0f340a3f879580e7981d97863bc299e33d71aa84
Closes-Bug: #1304695
'}]
commit_message:
libvirt: Refresh volume connection_info after volume snapshot

The following patch is related to the guest assisted snapshot
functionality.  When you take a snapshot of a volume
(e.g. GlusterFS) attached to a running instance, a new snapshot
file is created, i.e. volume-<uuid>.<snapshot-uuid>.  The
instance uses this file as the active volume.  If you shutdown
and restart the instance, nova will reattach the base volume
(volume-<uuid>) to the instance instead of the snapshot volume
(volume-<uuid>.<snapshot-uuid>).  The expected behavior is to
have the snapshot volume reattach to the instance.  This is
caused by stale data being returned from the database when
_get_instance_volume_block_device_info is called during
_power_on.  To fix this bug, this patch calls
refresh_connection_info to update the database in both
volume_snapshot_create and _volume_snapshot_delete methods of the
libvirt driver.

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/virt/libvirt/test_libvirt.py

Change-Id: I0f340a3f879580e7981d97863bc299e33d71aa84
Closes-Bug: #1304695

commit_message:
Moving eventlet.hubs.use_hub call up

Under the design concept of eventlet, we need to call
eventlet.hubs.use_hub() before the application starts
doing any I/O. And it makes custom log handlers register
correct event listeners.

Closes-bug: 1247889
Change-Id: I3d43021c8cb6ed630123781f3686d62e5159edfc
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

[{'created': '2014-06-02 17:06:04.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes Hyper-V iSCSI target login method

Hyper-V is trying to log in to portals/targets every time a volume
is attached, even if the portal/target was already connected. This
is not an issue with most volume backends, but it causes the attach
to fail when using Storwize as a Cinder backend.

This patch fixes the issue by checking if the target or portal is
already connected, and simply perform an update in this case,
instead of attempting to create a new connection.

Also, a retry loop is introduced for the case when the iSCSI target
login fails. As in this loop it is checked whether or not the
operation completed successfully, this method does not rely anymore
only on a sleep interval to ensure that the connection to the target
has been made. Even so, on V2 volume utilities, the sleep interval
is still needed to avoid having a new connection attempt before the
last one finished.

The method which gets the according mounted disk must raise an
exception when the device number is -1, which signifies that the
disk has not been mounted properly.

Co-Authored-By: Jay Bryant <jsbryant@us.ibm.com>

Closes-bug: #1221525

Change-Id: I92d2a586704fa3e857f46432bb571c81e86d183b
(cherry picked from commit ea91ad2b2317cb88fb14c0cdaf31187eca93ff57)
'}]
commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V iSCSI target login method

Hyper-V is trying to log in to portals/targets every time a volume
is attached, even if the portal/target was already connected. This
is not an issue with most volume backends, but it causes the attach
to fail when using Storwize as a Cinder backend.

This patch fixes the issue by checking if the target or portal is
already connected, and simply perform an update in this case,
instead of attempting to create a new connection.

Also, a retry loop is introduced for the case when the iSCSI target
login fails. As in this loop it is checked whether or not the
operation completed successfully, this method does not rely anymore
only on a sleep interval to ensure that the connection to the target
has been made. Even so, on V2 volume utilities, the sleep interval
is still needed to avoid having a new connection attempt before the
last one finished.

The method which gets the according mounted disk must raise an
exception when the device number is -1, which signifies that the
disk has not been mounted properly.

Co-Authored-By: Jay Bryant <jsbryant@us.ibm.com>

Closes-bug: #1221525

Change-Id: I92d2a586704fa3e857f46432bb571c81e86d183b
(cherry picked from commit ea91ad2b2317cb88fb14c0cdaf31187eca93ff57)

commit_message:
Don't specify admin_token in paste config

This is not a value that is going to be useful on other systems and
shouldn't be included in the default or test pipelines.

The two similar commits were squashed together here.

(cherry picked from commit ae696056fbac7d74a395710934950e0013cd4d37)
(cherry picked from commit 9db80e79ea3e687000121729648af7e79b7b2d78)

Closes-Bug: #1299332
Change-Id: I714539b7536965fa08a3ddc64493b481df7397e3

commit_message:
Check rescue_server action attributes of Nova APIs

This patch adds the JSON schema for Nova V2 & V3 rescue server
action APIs response and validate the response with added JSON schema
to block the backward incompatibility change in the future.

For V3 API, "admin_password" in response body is depend on config
variable "enable_instance_password". So schema and request
is adjusted accordingly.
NOTE - V2 rescue API's response does not on above config variable.

The response body of rescue server V2 APIs is below:
{
    "adminPass": "%(password)s"
}

The response body of rescue server V3 APIs is below:
If CONF.enable_instance_password is true-
{
    "admin_password": "%(password)s"
}
Else
    {}

Partially implements blueprint nova-api-attribute-test

Change-Id: I85f18eaa58bfef1871100816f97487f9fa9bc0ee

commit_message:
Use None instead of mutables in test method params defaults

Mutables in the method params defaults might cause errors and
that's why it's anti-pattern in most of the cases and should be
removed.

Change-Id: Ie9897aae6e95962e0991ac9d9fc5c175f2da12a4

commit_message:
Add context as param to cleanup function

In nova-network, when we start
to cleanup the stuffs it did when handle exception
but the function is following in objects/fixed_ips.py
def disassociate(self, context):
so the context param is lost and it can lead to problem.

Change-Id: I66a1681f47fc69bf0fd92137ee27481659833bef
Closes-Bug: #1350268

Specify memcache servers for nova::controller

Specify all memcache servers instead of 127.0.0.1.
Otherwise, noVNC service will be broken

Change-Id: Id1bb3fb36aab812d8c52a16bddc27231619a684b
Closes-Bug: 1350706
Closes-Bug: 1323705

commit_message:
Make Ironic the default and deprecate nova-bm

nova-baremetal has been deprecated by Nova and slated for removal.
The least we can do is be aligned with this!

Change-Id: Icb66ebe3237e47dfe5eb7967e64c67bdaa7eac51

commit_message:
Add logstash-web element

Configures logstash-web to start as a service. The upstream init script
has an error around CONF_DIR, which is unused anyway, so that has been
fixed. Additionally the http port has been changed to 19292 so as not to
conflict with Glance.

Advances blueprint logstash.

Change-Id: I4d552aab27fe9afab43c01364fad9d816c86ea1f

commit_message:
Data Processing: Allowing for HDFS data sources without hdfs://

Now that HDFS data sources can be either full URLs
or paths relative to the cluster itself, it is no
longer desirable to force "hdfs://" at the start
of hdfs data sources.
* No longer force the prefix on the create form
* For swift, we now check to see that the location
  starts with swift://, if it doesn't we add it

Change-Id: I62a8fbad6d55505c2b82561fe3de706e5069c83f
Closes-Bug:  bug #1336283

commit_message:
Avoid errors in log when neutron tests are skipped

The BaseNetworkTest class setUpClass() method will initialize
various class attributes which the tearDownClass() method
expects to exist. Unfortunately when Neutron is not
available, the entire of the setUpClass() method is skipped,
but tearDownClass() still runs. This causes the logs to get
polluted with errors about missing attributes during
tearDownClass(). eg

ERROR tempest.test [-] tearDownClass failed: type object
 'DHCPAgentSchedulersTestJSON' has no attribute 'ipsecpolicies'
TRACE tempest.test     for ipsecpolicy in cls.ipsecpolicies:

Make the tearDownClass() code be conditional on neutron
being enabled too.

Change-Id: I042ca5c47e5c1e8d1042754fd7f36036a40b2f03
